WEBVTT

01:07.026 --> 01:11.405
<i>I shall never forget
the weekend Laura died.</i>

01:11.489 --> 01:17.203
<i>A silver sun burned through the sky
like a huge magnifying glass.</i>

01:17.286 --> 01:21.499
<i>It was the hottest Sunday
in my recollection.</i>

01:21.582 --> 01:25.670
<i>I felt as if I were the only human being
left in New York.</i>

01:27.463 --> 01:30.967
<i>For with Laura's
horrible death, I was alone.</i>

01:32.385 --> 01:35.346
<i>I, Waldo Lydecker</i>

01:35.429 --> 01:38.432
<i>was the only one who really knew her</i>

01:40.017 --> 01:44.105
<i>and I had just begun
to write Laura's story when</i>

01:44.188 --> 01:47.525
<i>another of those detectives
came to see me.</i>

01:48.526 --> 01:50.528
<i>I had him wait.</i>

01:53.531 --> 01:56.284
<i>I could watch him
through the half-open door.</i>

02:10.006 --> 02:13.009
<i>I noted that his attention
was fixed upon my clock.</i>

02:14.135 --> 02:16.470
<i>There was only one other in existence</i>

02:16.554 --> 02:19.265
<i>and that was in Laura's apartment,</i>

02:19.473 --> 02:22.393
<i>in the very room
where she was murdered.</i>

02:26.605 --> 02:29.442
Careful there. That stuff is priceless.

02:30.609 --> 02:32.611
Come in here, please.

02:39.368 --> 02:41.287
Mr. Lydecker?

02:41.370 --> 02:43.748
Ah, you recognize me. How splendid.

02:43.831 --> 02:45.833
Sit down, please.

02:48.419 --> 02:50.713
Nice little place
you have here, Mr. Lydecker.

02:50.796 --> 02:54.008
It's lavish, but I call it home.

02:54.133 --> 02:57.261
I suppose you're here
about the Laura Hunt murder.

02:57.636 --> 02:59.597
Yesterday morning,
after Laura's body was found,

02:59.680 --> 03:02.808
I was questioned
by Sergeants McAvity and Schultz,

03:02.933 --> 03:04.935
and I stated,

03:05.019 --> 03:08.189
"On Friday night, Laura had a dinner
engagement with me

03:08.314 --> 03:11.525
"after which she was ostensibly
going out of town.

03:11.734 --> 03:15.780
"She phoned and canceled
our engagement at exactly 7:00."

03:15.905 --> 03:17.990
- After that I...
- You "ate a lonely dinner,

03:18.074 --> 03:21.285
"then got into the tub to read."

03:21.369 --> 03:23.162
Why did you write it down?

03:23.287 --> 03:25.539
Afraid you'd forget it?

03:25.623 --> 03:29.210
I am the most widely
misquoted man in America.

03:29.293 --> 03:31.837
When my friends do it, I resent it.

03:31.921 --> 03:35.299
From Sergeants McAvity and Schultz,
I should find it intolerable.

03:35.383 --> 03:38.094
Hand me that washcloth, please, Mr.

03:38.177 --> 03:40.388
Mr.

03:40.471 --> 03:42.390
McPherson.

03:42.473 --> 03:45.226
McPherson. McPherson.

03:45.309 --> 03:48.229
Mark McPherson,
the siege of Babylon, Long Island.

03:48.312 --> 03:50.593
The gangster with the machine gun.
Killed three policemen.

03:50.648 --> 03:53.109
I told the story over the air
and wrote a column about it.

03:53.192 --> 03:55.194
Are you the one
with the leg full of lead,

03:55.277 --> 03:57.571
- the man who walked right in and got him?
- Yeah.

03:58.197 --> 04:00.366
Well, well. Hand me my robe, please.

04:04.787 --> 04:07.581
You have a pretty good memory,
Mr. Lydecker.

04:07.665 --> 04:11.460
I always liked that detective
with the silver shinbone.

04:11.544 --> 04:15.798
Thanks. I hope you won't have any reason
to change your mind about me.

04:15.881 --> 04:18.884
- Have you any more questions?
- Yeah, just one.

04:18.968 --> 04:21.429
Two years ago,
in your October 17 column,

04:21.512 --> 04:23.681
you started out to write a book review,

04:23.764 --> 04:24.824
but at the bottom of the column,

04:24.849 --> 04:27.351
you switched over
to the Harrington murder case.

04:27.435 --> 04:31.605
Are the processes of the creative mind
now under the jurisdiction of the police?

04:31.689 --> 04:36.485
You said Harrington was rubbed out with
a shotgun loaded with buckshot,

04:36.569 --> 04:39.363
the way Laura Hunt was murdered
night before last.

04:39.447 --> 04:41.365
- Did I?
- Yeah.

04:42.158 --> 04:44.452
But he was really killed
with a sash weight.

04:44.535 --> 04:48.456
How ordinary.
My version was obviously superior.

04:48.539 --> 04:50.499
I never bother with details, you know.

04:50.583 --> 04:53.544
I do. Well, so long.

04:54.587 --> 04:57.006
Mind if I go with you?

04:57.089 --> 05:00.634
- What for?
- Murder is my favorite crime.

05:00.718 --> 05:02.761
I write about it regularly,

05:02.845 --> 05:06.849
and I know you'll have to visit everyone
on your list of suspects.

05:06.932 --> 05:09.018
I'd like to study their reactions.

05:09.101 --> 05:11.896
- You're on the list yourself, you know.
- Good.

05:11.979 --> 05:15.483
To have overlooked me
would have been a pointed insult.

05:15.566 --> 05:19.236
You're not the sort of man
one would insult, Mr. Lydecker.

05:19.320 --> 05:22.281
- Do you really suspect me?
- Yes.

05:22.364 --> 05:26.410
McPherson, if you know anything
about faces, look at mine.

05:28.913 --> 05:32.082
How singularly innocent
I look this morning.

05:32.708 --> 05:35.419
Have you ever seen such candid eyes?

05:39.507 --> 05:42.676
Something you confiscated
in a raid on a kindergarten?

05:42.760 --> 05:47.014
Takes a lot of control.
Would you like to try it?

05:47.097 --> 05:49.433
No, thanks.

05:49.517 --> 05:52.353
Were you in love
with Laura Hunt, Mr. Lydecker?

05:55.105 --> 05:57.358
Was she in love with you?

05:57.441 --> 05:59.860
Laura considered me
the wisest, the wittiest,

05:59.944 --> 06:02.988
the most interesting man
she'd ever met.

06:03.072 --> 06:05.783
I was in complete accord
with her on that point.

06:06.825 --> 06:08.869
She thought me also the kindest,

06:08.953 --> 06:11.121
the gentlest,

06:11.205 --> 06:13.624
the most sympathetic man in the world.

06:13.707 --> 06:16.293
Did you agree with her there too?

06:16.377 --> 06:18.754
McPherson, you won't understand this,

06:20.005 --> 06:23.551
but I tried to become
the kindest, the gentlest,

06:24.468 --> 06:26.637
the most sympathetic man in the world.

06:26.845 --> 06:29.139
Have any luck?

06:29.223 --> 06:32.434
Let me put it this way.

06:32.601 --> 06:37.106
I should be sincerely sorry to see my
neighbors' children devoured by wolves.

06:37.231 --> 06:38.691
Shall we go?

07:03.007 --> 07:04.858
- Good morning, Lieutenant.
- Good morning, Mrs. Tread well.

07:04.883 --> 07:06.135
- Waldo.
- Good morning, Ann.

07:06.218 --> 07:09.513
- I've just taken over the Laura Hunt case.
- Won't you sit down?

07:10.264 --> 07:12.600
Thanks. I have all the reports,

07:12.683 --> 07:15.060
but there are a few more questions
I'd like to ask.

07:15.144 --> 07:16.812
Certainly. I'll do anything
I can to help.

07:16.895 --> 07:19.023
You were fond of your niece,
Mrs. Tread well?

07:19.106 --> 07:21.108
Why, I adored her. Cigarette?

07:21.191 --> 07:24.194
No, thanks. You collapsed when
you identified the body.

07:24.278 --> 07:28.365
I can quite understand that. A shotgun
loaded with buckshot, close range.

07:28.532 --> 07:31.619
- It's not very nice to look at.
- It was horrible.

07:31.702 --> 07:34.330
Her maid Bessie, I suppose
she was devoted to Miss Hunt?

07:34.413 --> 07:37.708
Oh, she worshipped her.
Laura had had her for years.

07:37.791 --> 07:40.961
I'll never forget her scream
when she saw Laura lying there.

07:41.337 --> 07:45.007
Did you approve of Miss Hunt's
coming marriage to Mr. Carpenter?

07:45.341 --> 07:48.719
Why? Shouldn't I approve?

07:48.802 --> 07:52.890
I don't know. What is your relationship
with Mr. Carpenter?

07:53.932 --> 07:54.975
What do you mean?

07:55.184 --> 07:58.062
What I mean is, he's been
a frequent guest in your home.

07:58.145 --> 08:00.898
Is he an acquaintance? Friend?
Are you in love with him?

08:01.023 --> 08:02.983
This is beginning to assume
fabulous aspects.

08:03.067 --> 08:05.819
Oh, shut up, Waldo!
What are you driving at?

08:05.986 --> 08:09.323
The truth, Mrs. Tread well.
Are you in love with him?

08:10.949 --> 08:14.995
Why, no. I'm very fond
of Mr. Carpenter, of course.

08:15.204 --> 08:17.331
- Everybody is.
- I'm not. I'll be hanged if I am.

08:17.414 --> 08:19.833
Oh, don't be so annoying, Waldo!

08:19.958 --> 08:21.960
Did you give Mr. Carpenter money?

08:22.252 --> 08:23.754
What do you mean?

08:23.837 --> 08:26.237
A couple of checks went through
your account endorsed by him.

08:26.298 --> 08:31.095
One on May 15 for $250.
One on May 22 for $400.

08:31.345 --> 08:34.556
Oh, that. I...

08:34.640 --> 08:37.059
I asked him to do
some shopping for me. That's all.

08:37.142 --> 08:39.019
Shelby's a very obliging fellow.

08:39.186 --> 08:42.940
For some time, also, you've been
withdrawing various amounts in cash.

08:43.065 --> 08:45.150
Sometimes 1,500.

08:46.151 --> 08:48.112
Sometimes 1,700 at a clip.

08:48.195 --> 08:50.698
Yes. I needed that money.

08:51.865 --> 08:57.037
The day you took out $1,500,
Mr. Carpenter deposited 1,350.

08:57.121 --> 09:00.582
When you withdrew 1,700,
he deposited 1,550.

09:00.666 --> 09:02.668
Maybe they were shooting crap.

09:03.001 --> 09:05.587
Oh, must I be insulted like this?

09:08.716 --> 09:11.969
I'm sorry, Mrs. Tread well, but I have
to find out about these things.

09:12.511 --> 09:14.321
Shelby needed some money,
and I lent it to him.

09:14.346 --> 09:16.724
That's all. After all, it is my money.

09:16.807 --> 09:19.167
- I suppose I can do as I please with it.
- Sure. Of course.

09:19.435 --> 09:22.121
Now, on Friday night, Mrs. Tread well,
you stayed home alone all evening?

09:22.146 --> 09:23.188
Yes.

09:23.272 --> 09:25.149
Why didn't you go to the concert
with Shelby?

09:26.483 --> 09:28.152
Because he didn't ask me.

09:28.485 --> 09:30.612
We were just talking
about you, Carpenter.

09:30.821 --> 09:33.699
- What a coincidence to find you here.
- This is Lieutenant McPherson.

09:33.824 --> 09:35.868
Oh, how do you do, Lieutenant?

09:35.951 --> 09:37.828
I didn't know you were here, Mr. Carpenter.

09:37.911 --> 09:40.330
As a matter of fact,
I was just lying down here.

09:40.414 --> 09:44.001
My hotel room was so hot, and then all
the people and reporters and telephone.

09:44.084 --> 09:45.836
You know how it is, Lieutenant.

09:45.919 --> 09:48.672
I've hardly slept a wink
since it happened.

09:48.756 --> 09:51.425
Is that a sign of guilt or innocence,
McPherson?

09:51.884 --> 09:55.137
I'm at your disposal, Lieutenant. I'm as
eager to find the murderer as you are.

09:55.220 --> 09:58.140
But what possible motive
could I have for killing Laura?

09:58.223 --> 10:00.617
Miss Hunt and I were going to be married
this week, you know.

10:00.642 --> 10:02.978
No, he doesn't know, and neither do I,

10:03.061 --> 10:06.815
- or you or anyone else alive.
- What do you mean by that?

10:06.899 --> 10:09.777
Laura had not definitely made up
her mind to marry him.

10:09.860 --> 10:13.864
She told me so herself last Friday when she
called up to cancel our dinner engagement.

10:14.114 --> 10:17.284
As a matter of fact, she was going
to the country to think it over.

10:17.367 --> 10:19.787
She was extremely kind,
but I was always sure

10:19.870 --> 10:24.166
she would never have thrown her life
away on a male beauty in distress.

10:24.249 --> 10:26.668
I suppose you've heard
losers whine before,

10:26.752 --> 10:28.754
especially in your profession, eh?

10:28.837 --> 10:30.517
Would you like
a bite of lunch, Lieutenant?

10:30.547 --> 10:32.591
That's very thoughtful,
the perfect host.

10:32.716 --> 10:33.967
- Waldo.
- You'd almost think

10:34.051 --> 10:35.052
he was in his own home.

10:35.219 --> 10:38.555
Shelby knows how distracted I am.
Would you, Lieutenant?

10:38.806 --> 10:40.891
Thank you, Mrs. Tread well,
but I've got to be going.

10:41.058 --> 10:44.812
But, Lieutenant. Well, I rather thought
you'd want to ask me some questions.

10:45.729 --> 10:48.148
Oh, yes. What did they play
at the concert Friday night?

10:48.232 --> 10:51.026
Oh, Brahms's First
and Beethoven's Ninth.

10:51.151 --> 10:54.404
Uh-huh. Have you got a key
to Miss Hunt's house up in the country?

10:54.488 --> 10:57.282
No, but I think there's one
up in her apartment.

10:57.366 --> 10:59.910
- Okay, I'll have a look.
- Perhaps I could help you?

11:00.577 --> 11:02.329
All right. Come along.

11:02.412 --> 11:04.873
I'll be seeing you, Mrs. Tread well.

11:08.877 --> 11:12.005
Extra! Extra!
Girl victim in brutal slaying!

11:12.089 --> 11:14.299
Extra! Girl victim in brutal slaying!

11:14.383 --> 11:16.927
Read all about it!
Girl victim in brutal slaying!

11:17.052 --> 11:19.763
Girl victim
in brutal slaying! Read all about it!

11:24.977 --> 11:27.062
All right. Break it up. Break it up.

11:28.897 --> 11:30.107
Ice-cold drinks!

11:57.050 --> 11:59.845
- The doorbell rang.
- What?

11:59.928 --> 12:03.223
As she opened the door,
the shot was fired.

12:03.432 --> 12:05.434
And how do you deduce that?

12:05.642 --> 12:08.770
She fell backward. The body was there.

12:09.813 --> 12:12.441
I thought you hadn't
been up here before.

12:12.691 --> 12:14.735
I saw the police photos.

12:23.911 --> 12:26.079
I guess I better try and find that key.

12:28.165 --> 12:31.668
McPherson, tell me, why did they have to
photograph her in that horrible condition?

12:31.752 --> 12:34.296
When a dame gets killed,
she doesn't worry about how she looks.

12:34.379 --> 12:37.466
Will you stop calling her a dame?
Look around.

12:38.884 --> 12:40.886
Is this the home of a dame?

12:42.971 --> 12:44.640
Look at her.

12:48.560 --> 12:50.354
Not bad.

12:50.520 --> 12:53.523
Jacoby was in love with her
when he painted it,

12:53.607 --> 12:55.859
but he never captured
her vibrance, her warmth.

12:57.694 --> 13:00.113
Have you ever been in love?

13:00.197 --> 13:03.200
A doll in Washington Heights
once got a fox fur out of me.

13:03.367 --> 13:06.828
Ever know a woman who wasn't
a "doll" or a "dame"?

13:09.081 --> 13:12.793
Yeah, one, but she kept walking me
past furniture windows

13:12.876 --> 13:14.795
to look at the parlor suites.

13:16.004 --> 13:18.757
- Would you mind turning that off?
- Why? Don't you like it?

13:18.840 --> 13:22.636
It was one of Laura's favorites.
Not exactly classical, but sweet.

13:23.220 --> 13:25.820
- You know a lot about music?
- I don't know a lot about anything,

13:25.889 --> 13:27.849
but I know a little
about practically everything.

13:27.933 --> 13:29.601
Yeah?

13:29.685 --> 13:31.687
Then why did you say
they played Brahms's First

13:31.770 --> 13:34.690
and Beethoven's Ninth
at the concert Friday night?

13:34.773 --> 13:37.501
They changed the program at the last
minute and played nothing but Sibelius.

13:37.526 --> 13:39.903
I suppose I should have
told you in the first place.

13:40.070 --> 13:42.698
I'd been working on that
advertising campaign with Laura.

13:42.781 --> 13:46.159
Well, we'd been working so hard,
I just couldn't keep my eyes open.

13:46.243 --> 13:48.870
I didn't hear a note at the concert.
I fell asleep.

13:48.954 --> 13:51.873
Next he'll produce
photographic evidence of his dreams.

13:51.957 --> 13:55.043
I know it sounds suspicious,
but I'm resigned to that by now.

13:55.168 --> 13:58.588
I'm a natural-born suspect just because
I'm not the conventional type.

13:58.797 --> 14:01.133
I wouldn't worry about it,
Mr. Carpenter.

14:01.258 --> 14:04.511
It sounds reasonable.
I fall asleep at concerts myself.

14:04.594 --> 14:06.179
Thank you.

14:07.806 --> 14:09.224
You found that key yet?

14:09.307 --> 14:13.020
No. I looked for it in the den,
but it wasn't there. It may be in here.

14:21.111 --> 14:22.696
Yes, here it is.

14:22.946 --> 14:25.407
I knew there must be
one around somewhere.

14:25.615 --> 14:28.118
The police are very fussy
about their inventories.

14:28.577 --> 14:31.621
That key isn't on the list of things
that were in that drawer yesterday.

14:32.247 --> 14:34.041
Then it's made a recent reappearance.

14:35.417 --> 14:36.668
You put it there, didn't you?

14:37.210 --> 14:39.629
- Yes.
- Why?

14:39.713 --> 14:42.399
It's just that I didn't want to give it
to you while Waldo was present.

14:42.424 --> 14:45.135
I have private reasons
that don't concern him.

14:45.218 --> 14:47.137
Everything about Laura concerns me.

14:47.804 --> 14:51.433
You have private reasons,
no doubt, to lie about the key.

14:51.516 --> 14:54.644
Waldo, for your own good,
I'm warning you to stop implying

14:54.770 --> 14:57.022
that I had anything to do
with Laura's death.

14:57.689 --> 14:59.608
Very well. I'll stop implying.

14:59.691 --> 15:01.276
I'll make a direct statement.

15:01.359 --> 15:02.861
All right, you asked for it.

15:03.487 --> 15:04.946
I wouldn't.

15:06.406 --> 15:08.867
Will you please stop dawdling
with that infernal puzzle?

15:08.992 --> 15:12.662
- It's getting on my nerves.
- I know, but it keeps me calm.

15:13.205 --> 15:14.456
Okay, let's go.

15:30.889 --> 15:33.100
This was our table,

15:33.183 --> 15:34.851
Laura's and mine.

15:36.353 --> 15:38.522
We spent many quiet evenings
here together.

15:41.274 --> 15:44.069
I remember we dined here the night
before her 22nd birthday.

15:45.570 --> 15:47.489
Just we two,

15:47.572 --> 15:51.368
happy, making plans for her future.

15:52.702 --> 15:53.662
Good luck.

15:53.745 --> 15:55.622
<i>But this was a far cry</i>

15:55.705 --> 16:00.544
<i>from the girl who walked into my life
at the Algonquin Hotel five years before.</i>

16:01.878 --> 16:04.214
Pardon me. Excuse me.

16:06.466 --> 16:08.468
Excuse me.

16:17.519 --> 16:20.564
Mr. Lydecker, how do you do?

16:20.647 --> 16:24.192
My name is Laura Hunt,
and I'm with Bullitt and Company.

16:24.276 --> 16:26.611
You know, the big advertising firm.

16:26.695 --> 16:29.614
And I'd like to talk
something over with you, if I may.

16:29.698 --> 16:33.910
You can hardly fail to realize that
I am engaged in eating my lunch.

16:33.994 --> 16:37.789
Yes, I know. I'm awfully sorry
to interrupt this way

16:37.873 --> 16:40.959
but it's so hard to get to see you
the regular way, and

16:41.042 --> 16:43.044
this will only take a minute, really.

16:46.089 --> 16:48.008
- Now, this is...
- Young woman,

16:48.550 --> 16:52.345
either you have been raised
in some incredibly rustic community

16:52.679 --> 16:54.389
where good manners are unknown

16:54.681 --> 16:57.100
or you suffer from the common
feminine delusion

16:57.184 --> 16:58.935
that the mere fact of being a woman

16:59.019 --> 17:02.105
exempts you from the rules
of civilized conduct.

17:03.273 --> 17:04.858
Or possibly both.

17:04.983 --> 17:07.819
Possibly, but here's
what I wanted to show you.

17:07.944 --> 17:10.030
It's for the Wallace Flow-Rite pen.

17:10.113 --> 17:14.201
I know my company would be glad to pay
you $5,000 if you'll endorse the ad.

17:14.284 --> 17:16.244
I don't use a pen.

17:16.411 --> 17:18.371
I write with a goose quill
dipped in venom.

17:18.455 --> 17:21.750
Yes, but this is a very fine pen,
Mr. Lydecker,

17:21.833 --> 17:23.460
the best on the market.

17:23.627 --> 17:26.504
Wouldn't you at least
consider endorsing it?

17:26.588 --> 17:30.550
I'll neither consider, endorse
or use the Wallace pen.

17:30.675 --> 17:32.886
I hate pens.

17:33.011 --> 17:36.348
If your employers wish me to publish
that statement in my column,

17:36.640 --> 17:39.392
you may tell them that I shall be
delighted to oblige.

17:40.018 --> 17:43.146
Oh, no. You mustn't do that.

17:43.396 --> 17:45.857
Don't blame Bullitt and Company,
Mr. Lydecker.

17:45.941 --> 17:49.653
They don't know anything about this.
It was my idea to see you.

17:51.488 --> 17:52.489
Indeed?

17:52.572 --> 17:56.910
Yes. I know they'd give anything down
at the office to get your endorsement,

17:56.993 --> 17:58.870
only they think there's no use asking.

17:58.995 --> 18:02.082
So I had this ad made up all on my own

18:02.207 --> 18:05.627
because I thought, well,
what's the harm in trying?

18:05.710 --> 18:08.129
There was always a chance
that you might, Mr. Lydecker.

18:08.463 --> 18:10.006
Just think what it would mean...

18:10.090 --> 18:11.925
You seem to be completely disregarding

18:12.008 --> 18:14.344
something more important
than your career.

18:14.427 --> 18:17.055
- What?
- My lunch.

18:19.516 --> 18:21.726
Do you really believe that?

18:21.851 --> 18:24.396
Implicitly.

18:24.479 --> 18:26.982
I never heard of anything so selfish.

18:28.024 --> 18:31.945
In my case, self-absorption
is completely justified.

18:32.028 --> 18:35.323
I have never discovered any other
subject quite so worthy of my attention.

18:35.949 --> 18:37.867
But you write about people

18:37.951 --> 18:41.329
with such real understanding
and sentiment.

18:42.831 --> 18:44.916
That's what makes your column so good.

18:45.709 --> 18:48.628
Sentiment comes easily
at 50 cents a word.

18:49.963 --> 18:52.215
Well, if that's the way
you really feel,

18:53.174 --> 18:54.968
you must be very lonely.

18:56.303 --> 18:59.556
Will you kindly continue
this character analysis elsewhere?

19:00.432 --> 19:03.351
- You begin to bore me.
- You're a poor man.

19:03.893 --> 19:06.021
I'm very sorry for you.

19:08.940 --> 19:11.693
<i>Naturally,
I was annoyed by the incident,</i>

19:12.444 --> 19:14.821
<i>but she had something
about her, that girl.</i>

19:16.197 --> 19:20.285
<i>I had to speak to her again.
I had to see her.</i>

19:20.577 --> 19:22.595
- Miss, would you mind if I...
- Just a moment, please.

19:22.620 --> 19:24.998
I'll tell Mr. Bullitt right away.
He's on the telephone.

19:25.123 --> 19:27.208
Thank you.

19:47.979 --> 19:51.566
Boy, Waldo Lydecker
to see Miss Laura Hunt.

19:53.610 --> 19:54.986
Announce me.

19:56.446 --> 19:58.823
Johnny, please tell
the gentleman I'm busy.

20:03.828 --> 20:07.415
Miss Hunt, I have something
to say to you.

20:07.624 --> 20:09.334
You've already said it, Mr. Lydecker.

20:10.085 --> 20:13.338
I wish to point out that you caught me
at my most difficult moment.

20:14.172 --> 20:16.800
Ordinarily I am not without a heart.

20:16.883 --> 20:18.510
Really?

20:18.635 --> 20:21.137
Shall I produce
X-ray pictures to prove it?

20:24.682 --> 20:26.559
I wish to apologize.

20:26.935 --> 20:28.686
Your apology is accepted.

20:31.439 --> 20:33.149
Good-bye, Mr. Lydecker.

20:33.316 --> 20:35.610
If you come
a little bit closer, my boy,

20:35.693 --> 20:37.904
I can just crack your skull
with my stick.

20:42.200 --> 20:46.496
And now, for reasons
which are too embarrassing to mention,

20:46.579 --> 20:48.081
I'd like to endorse that pen.

20:49.499 --> 20:51.543
Mr. Lydecker!

20:51.751 --> 20:53.211
Thank you.

20:56.131 --> 20:58.508
- You're a very strange man.
- What?

20:59.467 --> 21:02.554
You're really sorry
for the way you acted, aren't you?

21:03.638 --> 21:06.141
Let's not be psychiatric, Miss Hunt,

21:06.224 --> 21:08.852
but in a word, yes.

21:10.395 --> 21:12.188
It's very kind of you, you know.

21:12.397 --> 21:15.191
I'm not kind. I'm vicious.
It's the secret of my charm.

21:18.611 --> 21:20.780
But if you choose to think me kind,

21:21.865 --> 21:23.700
I'll call for you at 6:00.

21:25.618 --> 21:27.620
All right?

21:28.329 --> 21:30.081
All right.

21:34.002 --> 21:36.963
<i>Her career began
with my endorsement of the pen.</i>

21:37.046 --> 21:39.883
<i>I secured other endorsements for her,</i>

21:39.966 --> 21:42.343
<i>introduced her to important clients.</i>

21:43.636 --> 21:45.889
<i>I gave her her start</i>

21:46.097 --> 21:48.141
<i>but it was her own talent
and imagination</i>

21:48.224 --> 21:51.144
<i>that enabled her to rise
to the top of her profession</i>

21:51.227 --> 21:52.604
<i>and stay there.</i>

21:54.272 --> 21:56.733
<i>She had an eager mind always.</i>

21:57.692 --> 22:01.237
<i>She was always quick to seize upon
anything that would improve her mind...</i>

22:01.446 --> 22:02.989
or her appearance.

22:04.657 --> 22:06.910
Laura had innate breeding.

22:11.789 --> 22:14.459
But she deferred
to my judgment and taste.

22:15.835 --> 22:18.421
<i>I selected a more attractive
hair dress for her.</i>

22:21.591 --> 22:24.886
<i>I taught her what clothes
were more becoming to her.</i>

22:26.888 --> 22:29.140
<i>Through me, she met everyone.</i>

22:29.724 --> 22:31.768
<i>The famous and the infamous.</i>

22:32.477 --> 22:36.898
<i>Her youth and beauty, her poise
and charm of manner...</i>

22:36.981 --> 22:38.358
<i>captivated them all.</i>

22:39.234 --> 22:42.028
<i>She had warmth, vitality.</i>

22:42.820 --> 22:45.031
<i>She had authentic magnetism.</i>

22:46.616 --> 22:49.285
<i>Wherever we went, she stood out.</i>

22:50.119 --> 22:53.164
<i>Men admired her. Women envied her.</i>

22:54.082 --> 22:57.961
<i>She became as well known
as Waldo Lydecker's walking stick...</i>

22:58.253 --> 22:59.879
and his white carnation.

23:00.630 --> 23:02.173
<i>But Tuesday and Friday nights,</i>

23:02.257 --> 23:05.760
<i>we stayed home, dining quietly</i>

23:05.843 --> 23:08.054
<i>listening to my records.</i>

23:08.429 --> 23:10.598
<i>I read my articles to her.</i>

23:11.474 --> 23:14.477
<i>The way she listened
was more eloquent than speech.</i>

23:16.938 --> 23:18.648
<i>These were the best nights.</i>

23:20.525 --> 23:23.653
Then one Tuesday, she phoned
and said she couldn't come.

23:25.154 --> 23:26.906
It didn't matter, really.

23:27.782 --> 23:30.868
But when it happened again
the following Friday, I was disturbed.

23:33.663 --> 23:37.959
<i>I couldn't
understand it. I felt betrayed</i>

23:38.167 --> 23:41.129
<i>and yet I knew Laura
would never betray anyone.</i>

23:47.844 --> 23:49.846
<i>I walked for a long time.</i>

23:52.181 --> 23:55.351
<i>Then I found myself
before her apartment building.</i>

23:55.852 --> 24:00.106
<i>The lights were on.
It pleased me to know she was home,</i>

24:00.523 --> 24:02.567
<i>till I saw she was not alone.</i>

24:05.028 --> 24:09.240
<i>But I waited.
I wanted to see who he was.</i>

24:13.870 --> 24:17.332
<i>It was Jacoby, who had recently
painted her portrait.</i>

24:17.832 --> 24:19.751
<i>I never liked the man.</i>

24:19.876 --> 24:24.547
<i>He was so obviously conscious of looking
more like an athlete than an artist.</i>

24:25.131 --> 24:27.800
<i>I sat up the rest of the night
writing a column about him.</i>

24:28.384 --> 24:30.094
<i>I demolished his affectations,</i>

24:30.219 --> 24:33.556
<i>exposed his camouflaged
imitations of better painters,</i>

24:33.806 --> 24:36.017
<i>ridiculed his theories.</i>

24:36.392 --> 24:39.729
<i>I did it for her,
knowing Jacoby was unworthy of her.</i>

24:39.854 --> 24:43.232
<i>It was a masterpiece
because it was a labor of love.</i>

24:43.733 --> 24:46.903
Naturally, she could never
regard him seriously again.

24:48.404 --> 24:51.407
There were others, of course,

24:51.574 --> 24:53.534
but her own discrimination
ruled them out

24:53.618 --> 24:56.079
before it became necessary
for me to intercede

24:58.039 --> 25:01.000
until one night at a party
at Ann Treadwell's.

25:01.334 --> 25:05.254
<i>It was one of her usual roundups
of bizarre and nondescript characters</i>

25:05.380 --> 25:08.141
<i>- corralled from every stratum of society.</i>
- How are you this evening?

25:08.174 --> 25:10.927
This is Mr. and Mrs. Preston.
They've been waiting to meet you.

25:11.010 --> 25:12.553
How do you do?

25:15.598 --> 25:17.392
- Hello, Shelby.
- Excuse me, honey.

25:21.979 --> 25:23.773
You're Laura Hunt.

25:24.357 --> 25:27.902
- Yes?
- Hello. I'm Shelby Carpenter.

25:27.985 --> 25:31.072
- Want to dance?
- I'm not alone.

25:32.949 --> 25:35.743
Oh, him? I'll bet
he's still doing the polka.

25:35.827 --> 25:38.121
Excuse me, please. Yes.

25:38.955 --> 25:40.456
Betsy Ross taught it to me.

25:40.581 --> 25:43.084
- Hello, Waldo. Darling, how are you?
- Hello, darling.

25:43.167 --> 25:44.602
- I see you've met Shelby.
- Hello, Ann.

25:44.627 --> 25:46.879
- Unavoidably.
- He was awfully nice to me in Louisville

25:46.963 --> 25:49.298
at the Derby. His family's from Kentucky.

25:50.133 --> 25:52.051
Sharecroppers, no doubt.

25:57.140 --> 26:00.268
Louise. Louise, for the last time,
will you marry me?

26:00.351 --> 26:02.520
I won't, but I've saved
some chicken livers for you.

26:02.603 --> 26:04.647
Oh, you're an angel.
In the meantime, darling,

26:04.730 --> 26:06.816
you think you could
get this spot out for me?

26:06.899 --> 26:09.610
I can afford a blemish on my character
but not on my clothes.

26:10.153 --> 26:12.613
- Mmm. Couldn't eat another mouthful.
- I'm afraid it's rouge.

26:12.697 --> 26:14.699
- I'm afraid it's liquor.
- Louise. Oh.

26:14.824 --> 26:16.701
May I have a glass of milk for Mr. Lydecker?

26:16.784 --> 26:17.785
Of course, Miss Hunt.

26:17.869 --> 26:19.745
I forgot to tell you.
I also read palms.

26:19.829 --> 26:24.041
I cook, I swallow swords, I mend my own
socks, I never eat garlic or onions.

26:24.125 --> 26:25.918
What more can you want of a man?

26:26.002 --> 26:29.088
- Don't listen to that scalawag.
- I didn't expect to find him here, Louise.

26:29.172 --> 26:30.882
What do you mean? We're old friends.

26:30.965 --> 26:32.758
She feeds me, humors me, repairs me

26:32.842 --> 26:34.927
and refuses to marry me,
don't you, honey?

26:35.011 --> 26:36.929
- I do.
- She has good sense.

26:37.013 --> 26:39.657
- Now, wait just a minute. Thanks, Louise.
- You're wasting your time.

26:39.682 --> 26:41.976
- She's got good sense too.
- You're jealous.

26:44.353 --> 26:46.647
And what does it feel like,
Mr. Carpenter?

26:47.315 --> 26:49.567
What does what feel like, Miss Hunt?

26:50.109 --> 26:52.153
Living on the income from an estate.

26:52.487 --> 26:54.405
- Well, I, uh...
- Or don't you know?

26:54.530 --> 26:58.075
Well, I did, until the sheriff
took it over 1 O years ago.

26:59.035 --> 27:01.037
Why maintain the fiction? Why not work?

27:01.120 --> 27:04.290
Believe it or not, I asked
one of my many friends for a job once,

27:04.373 --> 27:07.460
executive of a big company,
2,500 employees.

27:07.543 --> 27:09.854
He could have pressed a button
and done it, but he just laughed.

27:09.879 --> 27:11.964
- He thought I was joking.
- Weren't you?

27:12.048 --> 27:15.092
No. When I convinced him, he got
embarrassed, said he'd phone me.

27:15.176 --> 27:19.305
That was months ago. Now whenever
he sees me, he looks the other way.

27:27.522 --> 27:30.149
- Do you really want a job?
- Yes.

27:33.236 --> 27:35.238
Oh, here you are.

27:35.321 --> 27:38.616
Laura, dear, I cannot stand
these morons any longer.

27:39.075 --> 27:41.869
If you don't come with me
this instant, I shall run amok.

27:43.079 --> 27:44.413
All right, Waldo.

27:45.915 --> 27:48.125
30 tomorrow, Bullitt and Company.

27:49.252 --> 27:50.795
You've got a job.

27:51.712 --> 27:55.341
<i>I concealed my
annoyance with masterly self-control,</i>

27:56.509 --> 27:59.762
<i>but I sensed a situation
which would bear watching.</i>

28:00.388 --> 28:03.015
Laura, take a look at this.

28:04.267 --> 28:07.770
Do you like it? Do you think it'll make
people want to bathe more often?

28:08.145 --> 28:10.523
It should. It's excellent.

28:10.898 --> 28:13.025
- There you are.
- Good night, Miss Hunt.

28:13.109 --> 28:14.252
- Good night.
- Good night, Mr. Carpenter.

28:14.277 --> 28:17.363
- Good night, honey.
- It's really very good. Who's the model?

28:17.446 --> 28:20.324
A girl named Diane Redfern.
You hired her yourself last week.

28:20.408 --> 28:21.784
- Don't you remember?
- Oh, yeah.

28:21.867 --> 28:24.870
Well, let's go, moon of my delight.
I am starved.

28:25.329 --> 28:26.789
You usually are.

28:27.665 --> 28:29.625
- I approve of that hat.
- You do?

28:30.459 --> 28:31.836
Mm-hmm. And the girl in it too.

28:32.503 --> 28:34.088
Thank you.

28:37.633 --> 28:39.468
I knew there was something on my mind.

28:39.594 --> 28:42.888
What is it? Oh, yes.
Will you dine with me tomorrow night?

28:43.139 --> 28:45.558
- Maybe.
- No, that isn't what's worrying me.

28:45.641 --> 28:47.618
- It's the next night.
- But, Shelby, I can't be...

28:47.643 --> 28:51.230
Good. What about three weeks from
tonight and all the nights in between?

28:51.314 --> 28:52.957
Don't you think
I have any other engagements?

28:52.982 --> 28:56.235
What about two months
from now and the month after that?

28:56.319 --> 28:59.530
- What about next year?
- That's all settled. What about breakfast?

29:00.489 --> 29:02.325
What about dancing?

29:02.408 --> 29:04.327
What about lunch? Beautiful lunches

29:04.452 --> 29:07.246
- day after day after day after day?
- What about work?

29:07.330 --> 29:10.458
Beautiful work,
day after day after day?

29:10.541 --> 29:12.251
Why, Miss Hunt, the way you talk.

29:12.460 --> 29:14.378
You'd think I was in love with you.

29:20.259 --> 29:22.511
Yes, Laura, I heard everything he said.

29:26.015 --> 29:27.558
I went to call for you.

29:29.393 --> 29:30.853
I'm sorry, Waldo.

29:31.646 --> 29:33.522
And that reminds me.

29:35.983 --> 29:38.694
Old Mother Hubbard has
something in the cupboard.

29:41.113 --> 29:43.115
The results of my private investigation

29:43.199 --> 29:45.701
of that sterling character,
Mr. Shelby Carpenter.

29:47.745 --> 29:50.247
By stooping so low, you only
degrade yourself, Waldo.

29:51.999 --> 29:55.586
Did you know that he almost went to jail
for passing rubber checks,

29:55.670 --> 29:58.130
that he was suspected of stealing
his hostess's jewels

29:58.214 --> 30:00.132
when he was a house guest in Virginia?

30:00.257 --> 30:02.927
Naturally they'd suspect him,
because he isn't rich.

30:03.928 --> 30:06.138
Those are only insinuations,

30:06.222 --> 30:08.391
the cheapest kind.

30:08.474 --> 30:11.102
These aren't only
insinuations, my dear.

30:11.227 --> 30:13.229
There you are. Read them.

30:15.106 --> 30:17.149
What of it?

30:17.233 --> 30:21.278
I know his faults.
A man can change, can't he?

30:21.362 --> 30:24.407
People are always ready
to hold out a hand to slap you down,

30:24.490 --> 30:26.409
but never to pick you up.

30:26.867 --> 30:28.577
All right, I'm helping Shelby.

30:28.661 --> 30:30.746
His past is his own affair.

30:30.871 --> 30:33.666
I only care about the present.

30:33.999 --> 30:37.128
Speaking of the changed Mr. Carpenter
in the present tense,

30:38.587 --> 30:41.382
he's now running around
with a model from your own office.

30:41.465 --> 30:43.718
Her name is Diane Redfern.

30:45.886 --> 30:49.223
I'm closer to despising you
than I thought I ever would be.

30:55.938 --> 30:59.150
I'm sorry. I should have
told you before.

30:59.734 --> 31:02.319
Shelby and I are going to be
married next week.

31:06.574 --> 31:09.785
I believe you presented him with
a cigarette case on his last birthday.

31:14.206 --> 31:15.666
Rather valuable, isn't it?

31:15.750 --> 31:17.293
Where did you get it?

31:17.501 --> 31:20.421
From the pawnshop where Diane Redfern
took it after he gave it to her.

31:21.046 --> 31:24.467
I don't believe it. He probably needed
money and was too proud to borrow.

31:24.550 --> 31:26.093
Carpenter proud?

31:27.720 --> 31:30.306
Perhaps that's why
the pawn ticket was in her name.

31:30.473 --> 31:32.313
Before this goes any further,
why, I'll just...

31:34.602 --> 31:36.061
He isn't home.

31:44.236 --> 31:46.155
He's dining at Ann Treadwell's.

31:46.322 --> 31:48.449
He can't be. He asked me to dinner.

31:48.657 --> 31:52.244
He would have canceled his appointment
with her if you had accepted.

31:52.328 --> 31:54.121
He treats her rather badly these days.

31:56.999 --> 31:59.126
I'm afraid she'll say he isn't there.

32:08.636 --> 32:10.638
Waldo,

32:11.847 --> 32:13.474
why are you doing this?

32:19.063 --> 32:20.898
For you, Laura.

32:22.942 --> 32:24.527
Shall we pay them a visit?

32:25.861 --> 32:29.406
He won't be there, Waldo.
I know he won't.

32:29.490 --> 32:31.951
All right. We'll see.

32:34.203 --> 32:37.206
Don't you want to take this little
bauble along in case he is there?

32:46.549 --> 32:47.749
- Good evening.
- Good evening.

32:47.842 --> 32:50.678
- I'm sorry. Mrs. Tread well is not home.
- We know, dear.

33:03.399 --> 33:05.067
Good evening.

33:10.447 --> 33:13.450
Hello, darling. I didn't expect
to see you tonight.

33:13.659 --> 33:15.077
There you are, my dear.

33:15.494 --> 33:18.163
In a moment of supreme disaster,
he's trite.

33:18.247 --> 33:21.083
You've been reading
too many melodramas, Waldo.

33:21.792 --> 33:24.169
I was just telling Ann
about our getting married.

33:25.045 --> 33:26.797
Well, have you two had dinner?

33:27.840 --> 33:29.300
Would you like a glass of wine?

33:29.425 --> 33:31.010
Why don't you sit down?

33:40.185 --> 33:44.023
I couldn't find out
if she saw Carpenter in the meantime.

33:44.231 --> 33:47.776
All I know is that on Friday
she had lunch with Diane Redfern.

33:49.278 --> 33:51.989
<i>What came
of it, I hoped to hear that night.</i>

33:52.156 --> 33:53.574
<i>I alternated between moods of</i>

33:53.657 --> 33:55.577
<i>over-optimism and over-pessimism.</i>

33:55.618 --> 33:58.120
<i>When the phone rang,
I had a foreboding of disaster.</i>

34:02.958 --> 34:05.586
I called to tell you, Waldo,
I'm frightfully sorry.

34:05.669 --> 34:08.047
I can't have dinner with you tonight.

34:08.255 --> 34:11.675
Oh, no, no. I'm not sick.
I'm just dreadfully nervous.

34:11.759 --> 34:14.345
I'm going to the country
for a few days.

34:14.595 --> 34:16.513
Yes. I'm afraid it's about Shelby.

34:17.556 --> 34:19.767
Oh, no. Please.
There's nothing you can do.

34:19.850 --> 34:22.353
I've got to think
this thing out for myself.

34:22.561 --> 34:26.649
I'm sorry. I'll call you
when I get back. Good-bye.

34:28.233 --> 34:30.611
It was the last time
I ever heard her voice.

34:32.154 --> 34:34.907
I was sure she had
too much pride to forgive him.

34:36.659 --> 34:38.160
But...

34:39.078 --> 34:41.497
Where does this Diane Redfern live?

34:42.164 --> 34:44.541
Brooklyn somewhere.
She's in the phone book.

34:46.835 --> 34:48.837
Come on. It's late. Let's get going.

34:49.838 --> 34:51.840
- Waiter.
- Yes, sir.

34:55.010 --> 34:57.012
- All right.
- Thank you, Mr. Lydecker.

35:01.517 --> 35:03.018
Good night.

35:07.147 --> 35:10.359
I shall never forgive myself for
letting her become involved with Shelby.

35:11.610 --> 35:13.028
It was my fault.

35:13.988 --> 35:16.031
I should have stopped it somehow.

35:16.824 --> 35:18.367
Well, it's too late now.

35:22.579 --> 35:24.248
Thanks for the wine.

35:43.100 --> 35:45.185
Hello. Mosconi's?

35:45.269 --> 35:48.522
This is Lieutenant McPherson,
Homicide Bureau.

35:48.605 --> 35:52.693
Laura Hunt had been buying her liquor
from you for several years, hadn't she?

35:52.776 --> 35:54.987
Yeah.

35:55.070 --> 35:58.365
Did she ever buy a brand of scotch
called Black Pony?

35:59.992 --> 36:01.910
Yeah.

36:03.078 --> 36:05.706
I see.

36:05.789 --> 36:07.916
Well, that's all
I wanted to know. Thanks.

36:08.000 --> 36:09.918
She's here, McPherson, the maid.

36:10.002 --> 36:12.463
Okay.

36:12.546 --> 36:15.299
- Come in, Miss Clary.
- Never mind the "Miss Clary" stuff.

36:15.382 --> 36:19.219
My name's Bessie, and I'm a domestic,
and I got nothin' to be ashamed of.

36:19.303 --> 36:21.388
Sit down, Bessie.

36:22.306 --> 36:24.391
Her letters.

36:24.683 --> 36:26.602
And her private diary.

36:27.770 --> 36:30.105
You've been reading them,
pawing over them.

36:30.189 --> 36:33.108
It's a shame in the face of the dead.
That's what it is. It's a shame.

36:33.192 --> 36:36.028
- Sit down, Bessie.
- I'll stand on my own two feet.

36:36.111 --> 36:38.197
Don't you go ordering me around.

36:38.280 --> 36:42.826
I ain't afraid of cops. I was
brought up to spit whenever I saw one.

36:42.910 --> 36:46.747
Okay, go ahead and spit
if that'll make you feel better.

36:52.628 --> 36:54.755
What do you want to know?

36:54.838 --> 36:57.174
What we all want to know,
who killed Laura Hunt.

36:57.257 --> 36:58.926
How would I know?

37:00.552 --> 37:02.387
You don't think I done it?

37:03.055 --> 37:05.933
I know you cops get crazy notions,

37:06.016 --> 37:08.393
but if you got any notion
concerning me...

37:08.477 --> 37:11.897
Ask anyone,
anyone who ever come to this house.

37:11.980 --> 37:13.899
I would have worked for her.

37:13.982 --> 37:15.901
I would have washed, ironed, scrubbed,

37:15.984 --> 37:19.696
done everything she wanted of me,
whether she paid me for it or not.

37:19.780 --> 37:23.742
And it wasn't only on account of the
thousand sweet things she done for me.

37:23.826 --> 37:26.370
It was because she was
so sweet herself,

37:26.453 --> 37:29.331
because she was a real fine lady.

37:30.833 --> 37:34.670
But you cops wouldn't know about that.

37:34.962 --> 37:40.259
But you do. That's all the more reason
why you should help me, Bessie.

37:40.384 --> 37:43.428
Do you happen to know how this got into
her liquor cabinet?

37:44.847 --> 37:46.849
I put it there.

37:47.015 --> 37:50.352
But she never bought cheap stuff like
that, not a lady like Miss Hunt.

37:50.435 --> 37:53.438
- No.
- When did you put it in the cabinet?

37:53.522 --> 37:55.440
- Saturday.
- Before the police came.

37:55.524 --> 37:59.027
- Was it there Friday night before you left?
- No.

37:59.153 --> 38:01.238
Are you sure of that?

38:01.446 --> 38:04.116
I cleaned out the cabinet on Friday

38:04.199 --> 38:06.201
and put the empties in the basement.

38:07.452 --> 38:09.955
Then somebody was with her
in the apartment Friday night,

38:10.038 --> 38:11.957
someone who brought that bottle.

38:12.040 --> 38:13.750
- Yes.
- Who?

38:13.834 --> 38:16.378
I don't know, but I didn't want anyone

38:16.461 --> 38:19.756
getting any wrong ideas about her,
God rest her soul.

38:20.507 --> 38:22.901
That's why I took it out of the bedroom
and put it in the cabinet

38:22.926 --> 38:24.887
before the police got here.

38:25.304 --> 38:27.472
And that ain't all I done.

38:27.556 --> 38:30.642
I washed out the glasses
and cleaned off the bottle too.

38:30.726 --> 38:32.828
Do you know what happens to people
who destroy evidence?

38:32.853 --> 38:34.229
I don't care.

38:35.981 --> 38:38.358
You ain't gonna tell
the newspaper reporters, are ya,

38:38.442 --> 38:40.402
and let them make up
their nasty stories

38:40.527 --> 38:42.112
and drag her name through the mud?

38:43.572 --> 38:46.033
Go ahead, but it won't do you any good.

38:46.116 --> 38:48.994
- I'll say you lied. I'll say...
- Take it easy, Bessie.

38:50.162 --> 38:52.414
Get me some ice and a setup, will you?

38:52.539 --> 38:54.583
All right.

38:54.666 --> 38:56.752
A couple of highball glasses.

39:01.882 --> 39:03.650
Good morning.
Lieutenant McPherson sent for us.

39:03.675 --> 39:05.594
- Good morning, Lieutenant.
- Hello, McPherson.

39:05.677 --> 39:07.905
This is quite a delegation.
I only sent for you, Carpenter.

39:07.930 --> 39:09.156
- I know.
- Shelby's dropping me off

39:09.181 --> 39:10.349
at the hairdresser's later,

39:10.432 --> 39:13.727
- so I thought I might as well come along.
- My excuse is equally feeble.

39:14.061 --> 39:16.230
I just popped in
to pay my dubious respects

39:16.313 --> 39:18.315
and inquire as to
the state of your health.

39:18.857 --> 39:21.084
- Insipid, I trust.
- I was just going to pour myself a drink.

39:21.109 --> 39:23.362
- Care to join me?
- A very nice idea.

39:23.445 --> 39:24.630
Shelby, wouldn't you like one?

39:24.655 --> 39:26.156
- I'll get it.
- Never mind.

39:26.240 --> 39:27.883
Bessie, would you bring
a couple more glasses?

39:27.908 --> 39:29.576
- Yes, sir.
- Hi, Bessie.

39:29.660 --> 39:30.953
What are you doing here?

39:31.036 --> 39:33.538
I'm paid up for the week,
and I'm working, regardless.

39:33.705 --> 39:36.875
- Would you like one, Lydecker?
- I see no reason to exclude myself

39:36.959 --> 39:38.418
if the host provides scotch.

39:38.502 --> 39:40.879
- This do?
- I presume it'll have to.

39:40.963 --> 39:43.131
How about you, Carpenter?
It's cheap, but it's potent.

39:43.215 --> 39:46.802
As a matter of fact, I don't think I care
for any. I'm not much of a daytime drinker.

39:46.885 --> 39:49.429
Uh-huh. That'll be all for you,
Bessie. You can go home now.

39:49.513 --> 39:51.181
But I... Yes, sir.

39:53.392 --> 39:54.910
I remember when Laura
bought these glasses.

39:54.935 --> 39:57.229
She loved them.
She loved all her things so.

39:57.646 --> 40:00.065
What are you going to do? Sell them?

40:00.148 --> 40:03.068
I don't know. I suppose so. Thank you.

40:03.151 --> 40:04.586
If I'm appointed
administrator of the estate,

40:04.611 --> 40:06.947
I shall probably just call in Corey.

40:07.030 --> 40:09.116
You mean Lancaster Corey,
the art dealer?

40:09.199 --> 40:11.285
Yes. He was a friend of Laura's.

40:11.368 --> 40:14.538
Let him dispose of everything.
It'll be less gruesome that way.

40:14.663 --> 40:17.708
Not quite everything, Ann.

40:17.833 --> 40:20.043
Two or three things in here
belong to me.

40:20.210 --> 40:22.671
This vase, for instance,

40:23.338 --> 40:25.507
and that, uh, clock, of course,

40:26.466 --> 40:28.218
and the antique fire screen.

40:28.510 --> 40:30.846
- I only lent them to Laura, you know.
- Oh, really, Waldo.

40:30.971 --> 40:35.309
Yes, really. This vase is the gem of my
collection. I intend to have it back.

40:35.392 --> 40:36.660
And the clock and the screen too.

40:36.685 --> 40:39.688
But they aren't yours. You gave them
to Laura. I won't permit it.

40:39.855 --> 40:42.357
Does an alleged fiancè
have any voice in this matter?

40:43.191 --> 40:44.609
I'll take the vase with me now

40:44.693 --> 40:48.196
and send someone to collect
the other things this very day.

40:48.947 --> 40:51.491
Nothing is leaving here
except you, Lydecker.

40:52.075 --> 40:54.911
Is that your quaint way
of indicating dismissal?

40:55.704 --> 40:58.707
We're all going anyway. I have to be
back at headquarters by noon.

40:58.790 --> 41:02.544
Lieutenant, I don't understand.
You sent for me, didn't you?

41:02.753 --> 41:04.421
- Yeah.
- Well, don't you want to see me?

41:04.546 --> 41:07.215
- Don't you want to ask me some questions?
- I'll be seeing you.

41:07.382 --> 41:09.134
- Well...
- I bid you good day.

41:09.259 --> 41:10.427
Come along, Shelby.

41:10.510 --> 41:13.055
Are you making any progress
on the case, Lieutenant?

41:14.973 --> 41:16.433
We're doing all right.

41:32.824 --> 41:35.619
- Hello, Mark.
- Go get something to eat. I'll take over.

41:35.702 --> 41:37.329
- Thanks.
- Take your time.

44:37.217 --> 44:38.843
Fred?

44:43.932 --> 44:46.268
- Yes?
<i>- What's the matter? Did you go to sleep?</i>

44:46.768 --> 44:49.229
This is McPherson.
Any calls come through?

44:50.855 --> 44:52.482
Well, keep listening.

44:52.857 --> 44:54.568
No. Nothing new.

45:01.283 --> 45:03.118
I happened to see the lights on.

45:04.786 --> 45:06.496
Have you sublet this apartment?

45:06.580 --> 45:08.540
You're here often enough to pay rent.

45:08.748 --> 45:11.126
- Any objections?
- Yes.

45:12.043 --> 45:14.045
I object to you prying
into Laura's letters,

45:14.212 --> 45:15.797
especially those from me.

45:16.047 --> 45:19.050
- Why? Yours are the best in the bunch.
- Thanks.

45:19.259 --> 45:20.969
But I didn't write them to you.

45:21.845 --> 45:24.264
Haven't you any sense of privacy?

45:25.223 --> 45:28.059
Murder victims have
no claim to privacy.

45:28.476 --> 45:32.022
Have detectives who buy portraits
of murder victims a claim to privacy?

45:33.940 --> 45:37.235
Lancaster Corey told me
that you've already put in a bid for it.

45:37.402 --> 45:39.529
That's none of your business.

45:39.904 --> 45:43.366
McPherson, did it ever strike you
that you're acting very strangely?

45:43.825 --> 45:47.370
It's a wonder you don't come here like a
suitor, with roses and a box of candy,

45:47.579 --> 45:49.581
drugstore candy, of course.

45:50.624 --> 45:53.084
Have you ever dreamed
of Laura as your wife,

45:53.168 --> 45:56.588
by your side at the policeman's ball,
or in the bleachers,

45:56.671 --> 45:59.674
or listening to the heroic story of how
you got a silver shinbone

45:59.758 --> 46:01.301
from a gun battle with a gangster?

46:03.595 --> 46:06.306
- I see you have.
- Why don't you go home? I'm busy.

46:08.350 --> 46:10.101
Perhaps we can come to terms now.

46:11.686 --> 46:14.981
You want the portrait.
Perfectly understandable.

46:15.065 --> 46:18.485
I want my possessions,
my vase, my clock and my screen.

46:18.568 --> 46:20.904
Also perfectly understandable.
Now, if you...

46:21.029 --> 46:22.572
Get going.

46:22.864 --> 46:26.368
You better watch out, McPherson,
or you'll end up in a psychiatric ward.

46:27.410 --> 46:31.373
I don't think they've ever had a patient
who fell in love with a corpse.

48:02.130 --> 48:03.631
What are you doing here?

48:06.968 --> 48:08.303
You're alive.

48:09.262 --> 48:11.639
If you don't get out at once,
I'm going to call the police.

48:11.890 --> 48:13.767
You are Laura Hunt, aren't you?

48:16.853 --> 48:18.271
Aren't you?

48:18.396 --> 48:21.024
- I'm going to call the police.
- Well, I am the police.

48:22.150 --> 48:23.693
Mark McPherson.

48:25.653 --> 48:27.197
What's this all about?

48:28.823 --> 48:30.241
Don't you know?

48:30.325 --> 48:32.327
- Don't you know what's happened?
- No.

48:33.995 --> 48:36.372
Haven't you seen the papers?
Where have you been?

48:37.665 --> 48:40.585
Up in the country.
I don't get a newspaper.

48:41.503 --> 48:45.006
- Haven't you got a radio?
- It was broken.

48:45.215 --> 48:46.674
What...

49:05.193 --> 49:07.737
Somebody was murdered in this room.

49:07.946 --> 49:09.864
Do you have any idea who it was?

49:10.156 --> 49:11.866
No.

49:11.950 --> 49:14.118
Who had a key to your apartment?

49:14.702 --> 49:16.746
Nobody.

49:16.871 --> 49:18.832
Are you sure?

49:19.582 --> 49:22.335
- When did it happen?
- Friday night.

49:26.256 --> 49:28.049
What are you going to do now?

49:28.383 --> 49:30.552
Find out who was murdered

49:30.677 --> 49:32.720
and then find the murderer.

49:36.474 --> 49:39.477
You'd better take off those wet clothes.
You might catch cold.

49:44.232 --> 49:46.192
Yeah.

49:55.660 --> 49:57.662
I found this in my closet.

49:57.745 --> 49:59.664
It's Diane Redfern's.

49:59.747 --> 50:02.625
It wasn't here when I left.
She's one of our models.

50:03.001 --> 50:04.419
Just about my size.

50:07.130 --> 50:08.756
Beautiful, wasn't she?

50:09.090 --> 50:10.633
Do you suppose...

50:14.804 --> 50:16.598
Sit down, please.

50:20.935 --> 50:23.605
This is Monday night.
You left on Friday.

50:24.022 --> 50:27.400
- Rather a long weekend, isn't it?
- Yes.

50:27.775 --> 50:29.444
What train did you take?

50:30.069 --> 50:31.613
The 7:26.

50:31.946 --> 50:34.449
- See anybody you knew on the train?
- No.

50:35.116 --> 50:38.703
- Then what?
- Then I got off the train at Norwalk.

50:39.454 --> 50:41.205
Saw nobody you knew
at the station either?

50:41.289 --> 50:42.582
No.

50:43.082 --> 50:44.417
Go on.

50:44.500 --> 50:47.295
Then I went to the garage
where I keep my car.

50:47.462 --> 50:51.174
It's a private garage.
Nobody saw me there either.

50:51.841 --> 50:53.134
Then I drove to my house.

50:54.010 --> 50:55.887
You were there three days.
What did you do?

50:56.387 --> 50:58.014
Work in my garden.

50:59.265 --> 51:00.892
You didn't go out in all that time?

51:01.309 --> 51:04.062
No. I had everything
I needed in the house.

51:04.812 --> 51:07.273
- Nobody came to see you?
- Nobody.

51:07.565 --> 51:09.067
I went there to be alone.

51:10.109 --> 51:12.509
Police were there on Saturday.
There was no one in the house.

51:13.821 --> 51:16.783
Oh, yes. Saturday, I took a long walk.

51:17.325 --> 51:19.160
I walked for hours in the woods.

51:21.329 --> 51:24.332
You were going to
marry Shelby Carpenter this week.

51:24.707 --> 51:26.167
Thursday, if I'm not mistaken.

51:29.170 --> 51:30.463
Yes.

51:30.964 --> 51:33.216
Yet you went away
just before your wedding,

51:33.341 --> 51:35.635
for a long weekend to be alone.

51:36.469 --> 51:38.930
I was tired. I'd been working hard.

51:39.013 --> 51:42.266
You know Shelby Carpenter has a key to
this apartment. Why didn't you tell me?

51:42.350 --> 51:44.602
I know nothing of the sort. He hasn't.

51:44.686 --> 51:46.688
How else did the girl
get into the apartment?

51:46.938 --> 51:50.483
You knew she was in love with Carpenter,
that he'd given her your cigarette case.

51:50.566 --> 51:51.985
You know all that, don't you?

51:52.151 --> 51:54.946
I knew that she was in love with him.
She told me so herself.

51:55.071 --> 51:58.282
- When did she tell you?
- At lunch last Friday.

51:58.366 --> 52:01.953
I also know she meant nothing to Shelby.
I understand him better than you do.

52:02.036 --> 52:04.372
She was found in your
dressing gown and slippers.

52:04.455 --> 52:06.916
That's hardly the regulation costume
for an impersonal chat

52:07.000 --> 52:09.544
between a man and woman
who mean nothing to each other.

52:09.836 --> 52:12.836
Did you know or did you suspect he was
going to bring her here Friday night?

52:12.880 --> 52:15.550
How could I? I don't know that he
brought her here. Neither do you.

52:15.675 --> 52:18.136
- You merely assume it.
- What other assumption is possible?

52:18.219 --> 52:21.556
Do you love Carpenter so much you'd risk
your own safety to protect him?

52:21.639 --> 52:24.475
My own safety? Do you suspect me?

52:24.642 --> 52:27.895
I suspect nobody and everybody.
I'm merely trying to get at the truth.

52:28.104 --> 52:30.314
I see you have been trying
to get at the truth.

52:30.398 --> 52:33.192
You've read things I never meant
anyone else to look at.

52:33.651 --> 52:35.111
Strictly routine.

52:35.236 --> 52:36.988
I'm sorry. Really.

52:40.616 --> 52:43.244
I'd better be going. I'll see you
in the morning, Miss Hunt.

52:43.536 --> 52:46.831
Oh, I must ask you not to leave
the house or use the phone.

52:47.165 --> 52:50.251
But... But I've got
to let my friends know I'm alive.

52:50.668 --> 52:53.129
Sorry, Miss Hunt,
but I must insist you do as I say.

52:53.254 --> 52:55.548
- Am I under arrest?
- No.

52:56.257 --> 52:59.844
But if anything should happen
to you this time, I wouldn't like it.

53:01.262 --> 53:02.930
All right. I promise.

53:03.056 --> 53:06.017
There's one more thing.
You may as well know what I know,

53:06.100 --> 53:07.727
some of it, at any rate.

53:07.810 --> 53:10.354
It'll save time and a lot
of unnecessary fencing.

53:11.564 --> 53:14.275
I know that you went away
to make up your mind

53:17.195 --> 53:20.698
whether you'd marry
Shelby Carpenter or not.

53:22.033 --> 53:24.744
What did you decide? I want the truth.

53:26.913 --> 53:28.581
I decided not to marry him.

53:30.333 --> 53:32.502
I'll see you in the morning.
Good night.

53:32.752 --> 53:34.212
Good night.

53:48.851 --> 53:51.979
Really? Does McPherson know that?

53:52.313 --> 53:55.024
Uh-huh. Well, okay. Good-bye.

53:56.442 --> 53:58.945
Say, Mark, that was
the medical examiner's report.

53:59.070 --> 54:02.406
It wasn't Laura Hunt. It was Diane
Redfern that was bumped off upstairs.

54:02.573 --> 54:05.243
- Kinda balls things up, doesn't it?
- Yeah.

54:05.326 --> 54:07.428
Say, you're not taking it too hard.

54:07.453 --> 54:09.831
Wait a minute.

54:10.164 --> 54:12.583
<i>- Hello?
- This is Laura. I've...</i>

54:12.667 --> 54:14.602
<i>Don't say anything on the phone.
Meet me right away.</i>

54:14.627 --> 54:16.629
<i>I'll wait for you in my car
in front of Bullitt's.</i>

54:17.880 --> 54:19.507
- Was that...
- Yeah.

54:19.966 --> 54:21.759
Dames are always
pulling a switch on you.

54:22.301 --> 54:23.636
Stand by.

54:41.696 --> 54:43.573
You follow her. I'm gonna tail him.

55:36.083 --> 55:38.603
Are you taking it down
or putting it away, Carpenter?

55:51.849 --> 55:54.602
- It's been fired lately.
- Yes. I killed some rabbits with it.

55:54.769 --> 55:57.521
- When?
- Oh, a while back. I don't know exactly.

55:57.605 --> 55:59.357
You know about guns, don't you?

55:59.440 --> 56:02.276
- Yes.
- How come you didn't clean it afterward?

56:02.360 --> 56:05.112
I don't know. I forgot, I suppose.

56:05.363 --> 56:08.699
- Your initials?
- Yes. I gave it to Laura for protection.

56:08.991 --> 56:11.035
She didn't want it, but I insisted.

56:11.452 --> 56:13.913
This house is rather isolated,
as you see.

56:14.080 --> 56:16.540
- Did you teach her how to use it?
- No.

56:16.791 --> 56:20.294
- Does she know how?
- I don't know. It didn't occur to me to ask.

56:20.503 --> 56:22.672
You're a vague sort of a fellow,
aren't you, Carpenter?

56:22.797 --> 56:26.259
I've spent very little time in observing
my own character, Mr. McPherson.

56:26.342 --> 56:29.103
You haven't borrowed it lately?
You didn't just bring it back tonight?

56:29.136 --> 56:32.181
You followed me here.
You saw me come in. You ought to know.

56:33.057 --> 56:35.977
You, uh, realize
the spot you're in, Carpenter?

56:36.978 --> 56:38.980
You took that poor girl
to Miss Hunt's apartment.

56:39.063 --> 56:41.440
You knew all along
it was she who was murdered.

56:43.317 --> 56:46.696
Didn't you know Laura Hunt would come
back any day and spill the whole thing?

56:48.656 --> 56:50.366
Or did you plan to kill her too,

56:50.449 --> 56:53.494
hide the body someplace
and cover up your first crime?

56:53.577 --> 56:55.371
You're being fantastic, McPherson.

56:57.164 --> 56:59.667
You took a bottle of Black Pony
to her house Friday night.

57:00.042 --> 57:01.961
I took it there over a week ago.

57:02.169 --> 57:05.256
Bessie said it wasn't there Friday
night. It was Saturday morning.

57:05.339 --> 57:06.924
I can't help what Bessie said.

57:10.177 --> 57:13.139
- Where's the key to her apartment?
- I haven't got it.

57:13.222 --> 57:15.683
What did you do with it,
give it back to her tonight?

57:16.934 --> 57:17.935
I never had one.

57:18.227 --> 57:20.896
You didn't take the bottle
of scotch to her house Friday night.

57:20.980 --> 57:23.165
You haven't got a key to her apartment.
How did you get in?

57:23.190 --> 57:24.910
- Well, I...
- You had a key, and I know it.

57:24.942 --> 57:27.361
- Now, come on, Carpenter. Spill it.
- I...

57:28.988 --> 57:32.074
Laura kept a duplicate key
at her office. I went over and got it.

57:32.533 --> 57:36.329
I'd asked Diane to dine with me. I wanted
to have it out with her once and for all.

57:36.579 --> 57:40.541
You know, she thought... Well,
she thought she was in love with me.

57:41.042 --> 57:44.295
Well, we couldn't go on talking
in public places. She was too upset.

57:44.462 --> 57:47.182
I couldn't go to her room, and I didn't
want to take her to my hotel.

57:47.256 --> 57:49.300
- So we went to Laura's.
- Yeah?

57:49.592 --> 57:51.594
We talked there for about three hours,

57:52.094 --> 57:54.930
- and then the doorbell rang and...
- Go on.

57:55.389 --> 57:58.100
Diane was frightened.
But knowing Laura as I've known her,

57:58.184 --> 58:00.144
I've learned to be
surprised at nothing.

58:00.478 --> 58:01.645
What do you mean by that?

58:01.729 --> 58:03.497
Her friends would come to her
with their troubles

58:03.522 --> 58:05.733
at all hours of the day or night.

58:05.816 --> 58:08.235
I asked Diane to answer the door.

58:08.402 --> 58:09.570
Why didn't you go yourself?

58:09.653 --> 58:12.281
Supposing one of Laura's friends
had found me there.

58:12.365 --> 58:15.201
- Why open the door at all?
- They must have seen the light.

58:15.326 --> 58:18.037
What about the girl? Diane,
what about her reputation?

58:18.120 --> 58:21.665
I asked her to tell them Laura had let
her the apartment while she was away.

58:21.832 --> 58:24.085
Anybody that knew Laura
would have believed that.

58:24.293 --> 58:27.129
- Yeah. Go on.
- Well, then the doorbell rang again.

58:27.713 --> 58:30.508
I could hear Diane's mules,
Laura's they were

58:30.591 --> 58:33.594
clattering across the bare boards
between the rugs.

58:33.677 --> 58:36.180
Then there was a moment's silence
and then a shot.

58:37.264 --> 58:39.058
It was an awful explosion.

58:40.184 --> 58:42.770
By the time I reached her,
the door was closed.

58:43.270 --> 58:45.898
- She lay there on the floor.
- Did you go out to see who it was?

58:45.981 --> 58:49.735
No. I was too confused, too horrified,
incapable of doing anything.

58:49.944 --> 58:53.155
The room was dark. I saw only
a vague heap lying on the floor.

58:54.031 --> 58:57.076
I don't think
I fully grasped the situation.

58:57.201 --> 59:00.329
I think I called her name,
but I'm not sure. I...

59:00.454 --> 59:03.624
I remember kneeling on the floor,
feeling her heart.

59:05.251 --> 59:07.044
My first instinct
was to call the police.

59:07.128 --> 59:09.130
- Why didn't you?
- I don't know.

59:09.213 --> 59:12.425
Or rather, I was afraid,
not only for myself, but for Laura.

59:12.633 --> 59:17.096
In a panicky sort of way, I felt I must
keep out of this to keep Laura out of it.

59:17.179 --> 59:19.348
I know now how foolish
and hopeless it was,

59:19.432 --> 59:22.017
but there was only
one thing on my mind,

59:22.101 --> 59:24.687
the safety of a person whose life
was dearer to me than my own.

59:24.770 --> 59:26.480
Don't you understand that?

59:26.689 --> 59:28.190
Did you think Laura had done it?

59:29.066 --> 59:32.027
- Did you?
- I don't remember what I thought.

59:32.445 --> 59:34.780
- Do you think so now?
- No.

59:35.281 --> 59:37.158
- But you didn't?
- No.

59:37.491 --> 59:40.786
On Saturday, when our men went to the
hotel to tell you that Laura was dead,

59:40.870 --> 59:44.790
- you seemed sincerely shocked.
- I was. I hadn't expected that mistake.

59:44.874 --> 59:46.959
But you had your alibi ready
no matter who was dead.

59:47.126 --> 59:49.670
Yet you knew the minute
Laura got back it wouldn't stick.

59:49.920 --> 59:52.590
Don't you see? I was incapable
of thinking that far ahead.

59:52.673 --> 59:55.217
I was incapable of thinking at all.

59:55.301 --> 59:58.762
I was groping for some way
to keep Laura's name out of it.

59:58.846 --> 01:00:03.017
I was heartbroken about Diane
and panic-stricken about Laura.

01:00:03.559 --> 01:00:06.020
I haven't slept a full two hours
since this thing happened.

01:00:06.145 --> 01:00:09.273
Let's get back to the present. What did
you and Laura talk about tonight?

01:00:09.607 --> 01:00:11.942
I told her the whole story,
just as I've told you.

01:00:13.611 --> 01:00:16.046
She phoned you after she promised me
she wouldn't call anybody.

01:00:16.071 --> 01:00:17.156
What did she want?

01:00:17.239 --> 01:00:19.283
It's perfectly natural
she should want to see me

01:00:19.366 --> 01:00:21.202
especially after what's happened.

01:00:21.285 --> 01:00:23.888
Why don't you tell the truth? She sent
you here to get rid of this gun.

01:00:23.913 --> 01:00:27.249
She did not. It was my own idea.
She doesn't even know I'm here.

01:00:34.048 --> 01:00:36.884
- It works fine, doesn't it?
- Yes. Did you think it wouldn't?

01:00:38.385 --> 01:00:40.930
I hoped it wouldn't.
All right. Let's go.

01:00:42.389 --> 01:00:46.435
- Well, am I under arrest?
- No, but you're not to leave town

01:00:46.519 --> 01:00:48.119
and it would be
foolish of you to try it.

01:01:08.249 --> 01:01:10.084
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

01:01:13.254 --> 01:01:14.964
- What's that?
- Breakfast.

01:01:15.130 --> 01:01:17.424
You didn't buy any food
when you went out last night.

01:01:23.806 --> 01:01:27.309
I'll fix some bacon and eggs.
Can you make coffee?

01:01:27.601 --> 01:01:30.104
Suppose you set the table
while I get breakfast.

01:01:31.605 --> 01:01:33.607
Do you always sound like this
in the morning?

01:01:33.691 --> 01:01:35.442
Don't tell me you can cook.

01:01:35.651 --> 01:01:39.780
My mother always listened
sympathetically to my dreams of a career

01:01:39.863 --> 01:01:41.574
and then taught me another recipe.

01:01:42.283 --> 01:01:44.994
Shh! Don't move.

01:01:49.873 --> 01:01:53.210
It's all right, Bessie.
It's all right, Bessie.

01:01:54.128 --> 01:01:55.546
She's alive.

01:01:56.297 --> 01:01:57.798
It's all been a mistake, Bessie.

01:01:57.923 --> 01:01:59.133
I'm not a ghost. Really.

01:02:00.926 --> 01:02:03.470
I found you, and you were dead.

01:02:04.054 --> 01:02:06.140
It was Miss Redfern's body you found.

01:02:08.309 --> 01:02:10.561
How about taking over here,

01:02:10.644 --> 01:02:12.563
fixing us some coffee and eggs.

01:02:12.980 --> 01:02:17.026
But I saw it with my own eyes.

01:02:18.485 --> 01:02:19.862
I don't understand it.

01:02:19.945 --> 01:02:22.156
Have you ever
heard a ghost ask for eggs?

01:02:23.157 --> 01:02:24.783
No, miss.

01:02:24.950 --> 01:02:26.327
You'll be all right, Bessie.

01:02:37.129 --> 01:02:40.007
Somebody should have warned her.
Poor Bessie.

01:02:40.341 --> 01:02:43.344
By the way, I've asked Waldo Lydecker
to come here this morning.

01:02:43.427 --> 01:02:45.387
- Did you tell him?
- No.

01:02:45.971 --> 01:02:47.681
Why not? It's brutal.

01:02:47.973 --> 01:02:49.475
I'm not doing it for fun.

01:02:51.352 --> 01:02:54.521
Why did you break your promise
and go out and see Shelby last night?

01:02:54.855 --> 01:02:56.732
You forced me to give you my word.

01:02:57.191 --> 01:02:59.693
I never have been and I
never will be bound by anything

01:02:59.777 --> 01:03:01.695
I don't do of my own free will.

01:03:02.029 --> 01:03:03.947
Redfern was in love with Carpenter.

01:03:04.990 --> 01:03:06.700
You admitted that last night.

01:03:07.034 --> 01:03:09.453
- May I have a match, please?
- Oh, I'm sorry.

01:03:09.870 --> 01:03:12.373
I also told you that
he wasn't in love with her.

01:03:13.582 --> 01:03:15.793
Just sit still.

01:03:23.550 --> 01:03:24.843
Hello, Lieutenant.

01:03:26.345 --> 01:03:28.639
- Morning, my darling.
- Hello, dear.

01:03:30.891 --> 01:03:32.559
Thank you.

01:03:32.726 --> 01:03:34.019
It's on again.

01:03:34.103 --> 01:03:36.143
Do I have to get a permit
from the police department

01:03:36.230 --> 01:03:37.898
to kiss my fiancèe good morning?

01:03:38.148 --> 01:03:39.692
So he made you change your mind.

01:03:39.900 --> 01:03:42.486
Speaking of changing one's mind,
Mr. McPherson,

01:03:42.569 --> 01:03:44.363
I have just come from my lawyer.

01:03:44.530 --> 01:03:47.282
Yeah? Did he tell you how much
you'll get off for good behavior?

01:03:47.366 --> 01:03:49.785
No, but he told me that anything
I may have said last night

01:03:49.868 --> 01:03:52.830
was said under duress
and can't be used against me.

01:03:52.913 --> 01:03:54.540
Besides, none of it was true.

01:03:54.748 --> 01:03:56.834
Smart lawyer you've got.

01:03:56.917 --> 01:03:58.936
Maybe he told you how that scotch
got up here Friday night

01:03:58.961 --> 01:04:00.629
after you'd bought it at Mosconi's.

01:04:00.713 --> 01:04:02.856
Maybe it was the lawyer
who brought Diane Redfern up here.

01:04:02.881 --> 01:04:04.675
Maybe...

01:04:10.723 --> 01:04:12.141
Well, McPherson,

01:04:12.266 --> 01:04:14.268
have you thought over
the deal I suggested?

01:04:18.397 --> 01:04:21.024
Waldo.

01:04:21.233 --> 01:04:22.776
Waldo.

01:04:26.822 --> 01:04:28.991
Right-hand pocket.

01:04:29.074 --> 01:04:30.784
You want a doctor?

01:04:31.076 --> 01:04:32.953
Right-hand pocket.

01:04:33.704 --> 01:04:35.289
We'd better take him into the bedroom.

01:04:48.260 --> 01:04:50.020
- What...
- Don't try and say anything, dear.

01:04:50.053 --> 01:04:51.472
Just be quiet.

01:04:54.683 --> 01:04:56.935
I think this is
carrying things too far.

01:04:57.019 --> 01:04:59.329
Your methods are vicious.
There ought to be a law against it.

01:04:59.354 --> 01:05:01.648
- Yeah?
- How does he feel now?

01:05:02.399 --> 01:05:04.109
It was a terrible shock. Poor darling.

01:05:04.193 --> 01:05:05.794
Don't tell me you're in love
with him too.

01:05:05.819 --> 01:05:08.322
Look here, fella. You're not to talk
that way to Miss Hunt.

01:05:08.489 --> 01:05:10.491
Shut up. Why do you cover up
for a guy like him?

01:05:10.657 --> 01:05:13.093
- Don't answer him, Laura.
- What story did he tell you last night?

01:05:13.118 --> 01:05:14.878
Don't answer him. Let him
talk to our lawyer.

01:05:14.912 --> 01:05:15.913
Our lawyer?

01:05:15.996 --> 01:05:18.056
- So now you're covering up for each other.
- Look at him, Laura.

01:05:18.081 --> 01:05:20.918
He's beginning to crack up.
He'd use anything to make an arrest

01:05:21.001 --> 01:05:22.801
just so he can be a big shot
in the headlines.

01:05:22.878 --> 01:05:24.963
I've got enough on you
to arrest you right now.

01:05:25.047 --> 01:05:27.049
Quick, McPherson, the handcuffs.

01:05:27.174 --> 01:05:29.593
- Trundle him off to the hoosegow.
- You keep out of this.

01:05:29.676 --> 01:05:30.928
You'll look nice in bracelets.

01:05:31.011 --> 01:05:33.055
Why don't you get down
on all fours again, Waldo?

01:05:33.138 --> 01:05:35.557
It's the only time you've ever
kept your mouth shut.

01:05:35.766 --> 01:05:38.519
I hope you'll forgive
my wee touch of epilepsy, my dear.

01:05:38.852 --> 01:05:40.395
It's an old family custom.

01:05:41.104 --> 01:05:44.358
Well, McPherson, what does
Laura's resurrection do to you?

01:05:44.483 --> 01:05:46.944
Too bad Diane Redfern
can't be resurrected.

01:05:47.486 --> 01:05:49.863
I'm afraid I've interrupted
what you call "a pinch."

01:05:50.489 --> 01:05:52.032
Do your duty, McPherson.

01:05:53.116 --> 01:05:55.911
You know, Lydecker,
you've made me change my mind.

01:05:56.411 --> 01:05:58.455
- For the moment.
- Well, in that case,

01:05:58.539 --> 01:06:00.582
we'll have time
for a little get-together.

01:06:00.707 --> 01:06:03.043
You'd better order some liquor
and some food, Laura.

01:06:03.168 --> 01:06:04.878
What for?

01:06:04.962 --> 01:06:06.642
People are coming
to celebrate your return.

01:06:06.797 --> 01:06:08.882
Ann and Bullitt and Corey. Everybody.

01:06:09.132 --> 01:06:12.010
- Who asked them to come?
- I did, when I was in there.

01:06:12.553 --> 01:06:14.346
I phoned my man,
and he's calling everyone.

01:06:14.471 --> 01:06:18.392
- Why did you do that, Waldo?
- A sense of the fitness of things, my dear.

01:06:18.559 --> 01:06:22.145
Perhaps our friend can weave all the
loose ends into a noose. Eh, McPherson?

01:06:22.229 --> 01:06:24.629
Sorry you went to all that trouble.
I've already called them.

01:06:29.403 --> 01:06:31.405
You're working yourself
to death, darling.

01:06:31.530 --> 01:06:34.908
- I haven't had a moment with you all day.
- It's a very thirsty crowd.

01:06:35.033 --> 01:06:37.244
Oh, after all,
it isn't your homecoming.

01:06:37.327 --> 01:06:39.830
Aren't you being
a little bit nasty, Ann?

01:06:40.080 --> 01:06:41.999
I feel nasty when I don't see you.

01:06:42.124 --> 01:06:45.669
Well, you look very sweet. That's
a completely wonderful hat, darling.

01:06:45.878 --> 01:06:48.463
Now, if you'll forgive me,
Laura wants a cocktail.

01:06:48.881 --> 01:06:51.258
- So do I.
- Well, here you go.

01:06:52.551 --> 01:06:54.761
Shelby, why don't you
come to your senses?

01:06:54.928 --> 01:06:58.307
You know it's all over between you
and Laura, or it soon will be.

01:06:58.599 --> 01:07:02.060
But you haven't lost me.
Why don't we get married now?

01:07:02.144 --> 01:07:03.579
Ann, dear, you don't seem
to realize the situation.

01:07:03.604 --> 01:07:04.855
Yes, but I do.

01:07:04.938 --> 01:07:08.317
That's why you need me. We'll get
the best lawyer that money can buy.

01:07:08.400 --> 01:07:10.777
When it's all over, we'll go away,
anywhere you want,

01:07:10.944 --> 01:07:11.984
and forget about all this.

01:07:12.112 --> 01:07:15.157
Thanks, Ann, but you see,
Laura needs me. Sorry.

01:07:18.785 --> 01:07:19.786
Uh-uh.

01:07:22.289 --> 01:07:24.124
- Laura.
- Thanks.

01:07:24.708 --> 01:07:27.461
If you don't mind,
I'd like a word with Miss Hunt.

01:07:27.628 --> 01:07:30.255
I don't mind.
Talk to her as much as you like.

01:07:31.548 --> 01:07:34.801
- I see he's taking a new tack.
- What do you mean?

01:07:34.968 --> 01:07:37.804
Trying to make you like him
to make you talk.

01:07:38.889 --> 01:07:41.475
Shelby, tell me, why did you go to...

01:07:43.310 --> 01:07:44.561
Excuse me.

01:07:47.481 --> 01:07:49.149
Why did you go
to the cottage last night?

01:07:49.358 --> 01:07:51.568
But don't you know? I was afraid

01:07:51.652 --> 01:07:53.320
you wouldn't think
of hiding that shotgun.

01:07:54.446 --> 01:07:56.573
- What shotgun?
- The one I gave you.

01:07:58.075 --> 01:07:59.993
You don't have to lie to me, darling.

01:08:00.494 --> 01:08:01.703
I'll stand by you.

01:08:09.544 --> 01:08:11.004
What's the matter, Laura?

01:08:11.838 --> 01:08:14.341
Oh, I guess I'm just nervous.
That's all.

01:08:15.425 --> 01:08:16.843
So am I.

01:08:18.261 --> 01:08:20.347
McPherson suspects Shelby.

01:08:21.682 --> 01:08:23.392
He seems to suspect me too.

01:08:25.143 --> 01:08:26.436
And so do some of my friends.

01:08:26.520 --> 01:08:29.022
You? Don't be absurd.

01:08:29.189 --> 01:08:31.858
- You could never do a thing like that.
- And Shelby?

01:08:31.984 --> 01:08:33.652
Oh, I don't think he did it.

01:08:33.777 --> 01:08:35.112
But he's capable of it.

01:08:37.698 --> 01:08:39.866
Are you as interested in McPherson
as he is in you?

01:08:40.283 --> 01:08:42.077
But, Ann, I only met him last night.

01:08:42.786 --> 01:08:44.496
That's more than long enough sometimes.

01:08:44.955 --> 01:08:47.791
Anyway, he's better for you
than Shelby. Anybody is.

01:08:49.751 --> 01:08:52.337
- Shelby's better for me.
- Why?

01:08:53.296 --> 01:08:56.216
Because I can afford him,
and I understand him.

01:08:57.217 --> 01:08:59.219
He's no good, but he's what I want.

01:09:00.387 --> 01:09:02.639
I'm not a nice person,
Laura. Neither is he.

01:09:03.265 --> 01:09:06.393
He knows I know he's just what he is.

01:09:07.019 --> 01:09:08.770
He also knows that I don't care.

01:09:10.105 --> 01:09:13.233
We belong together because we're
both weak and can't seem to help it.

01:09:14.693 --> 01:09:16.737
That's why I know
he's capable of murder.

01:09:17.779 --> 01:09:19.406
He's like me.

01:09:21.658 --> 01:09:23.577
No, dear, I didn't

01:09:24.411 --> 01:09:25.829
but I thought of it.

01:09:43.930 --> 01:09:47.184
Hello? Yes. Yes.

01:09:47.726 --> 01:09:49.311
Oh, it's for you, Lieutenant.

01:09:50.729 --> 01:09:52.314
Thank you, Bessie.

01:09:52.939 --> 01:09:54.524
McPherson.

01:09:56.151 --> 01:09:58.820
Yeah, I know. Don't worry.

01:09:58.945 --> 01:10:01.073
I told you I'd bring in
the killer today.

01:10:02.783 --> 01:10:04.993
Yeah. I was just gonna
make the arrest when you called.

01:10:06.328 --> 01:10:08.705
No, I can't tell you now.
I'm not alone.

01:10:10.665 --> 01:10:12.292
You'll see when I come in.

01:10:13.168 --> 01:10:14.753
Right. See you later.

01:10:35.190 --> 01:10:36.441
All right. Let's go.

01:10:37.067 --> 01:10:38.568
- You mean...
- Yeah.

01:10:38.735 --> 01:10:40.403
Oh, no!

01:10:42.364 --> 01:10:44.741
No. No, no.

01:10:44.991 --> 01:10:46.660
Not Miss Hunt.

01:10:47.035 --> 01:10:48.662
Please!

01:10:50.163 --> 01:10:51.748
Thank you, Bessie.

01:10:54.042 --> 01:10:55.418
Thank you.

01:10:56.670 --> 01:10:59.256
Now will you please be good enough
to go and get me my things?

01:11:00.173 --> 01:11:02.175
- Yes, miss.
- Laura.

01:11:03.760 --> 01:11:06.513
Don't worry, darling.
Let them accuse you.

01:11:07.013 --> 01:11:08.557
We'll fight them.

01:11:08.932 --> 01:11:12.811
I have every weapon,
money, connections, prestige.

01:11:13.019 --> 01:11:14.354
<i>And my column.</i>

01:11:14.437 --> 01:11:17.774
Every day, millions will read about you
and rally to your defense.

01:11:17.858 --> 01:11:20.569
You talk as if you wanted
to see her tried for murder.

01:11:20.694 --> 01:11:25.824
Yes. Rather than let you blacken
her name with suspicions and rumors.

01:11:26.491 --> 01:11:28.285
Try to prove her guilty.

01:11:28.368 --> 01:11:31.121
Get on the witness stand
with your poor shreds of evidence.

01:11:31.538 --> 01:11:34.374
I'll expose your cheap methods
you used on her.

01:11:35.959 --> 01:11:38.920
- Thank you, Bessie.
- Laura, I told you to watch out for this fella.

01:11:39.004 --> 01:11:41.214
- Can we go now?
- I warned you.

01:11:43.508 --> 01:11:46.553
It's too bad you didn't
open that door Friday night, Carpenter.

01:11:46.761 --> 01:11:49.347
- Wait a minute.
- Shelby!

01:11:52.309 --> 01:11:53.977
Oh, did he hurt you, darling?

01:11:54.561 --> 01:11:56.563
Darling.

01:11:58.106 --> 01:11:59.608
Ann.

01:12:03.862 --> 01:12:05.363
Come in.

01:12:06.615 --> 01:12:08.200
Sit down.

01:12:09.701 --> 01:12:11.578
- That'll be all, Gallagher.
- Yes, sir.

01:12:15.248 --> 01:12:19.419
All right. Let's have it. Look at me.

01:12:21.755 --> 01:12:24.174
What are you trying to do,
force a confession out of me?

01:12:24.257 --> 01:12:26.801
You've been holding out,
and I want to know why.

01:12:26.885 --> 01:12:28.720
It'll be easier for you
if you tell the truth.

01:12:30.388 --> 01:12:32.807
What difference
does it make what I say?

01:12:32.891 --> 01:12:35.060
You've made up your mind I'm guilty.

01:12:35.143 --> 01:12:38.939
- Are you?
- Don't tell me you have any doubts.

01:12:39.022 --> 01:12:41.691
Since you... Oh, I can't.

01:12:41.775 --> 01:12:43.944
Please. Do I have to have
those lights in my face?

01:12:50.283 --> 01:12:54.371
Thanks. No, I didn't kill Diane Redfern

01:12:55.038 --> 01:12:56.289
or anyone else.

01:12:57.874 --> 01:13:00.377
Then why...

01:13:00.460 --> 01:13:03.713
Why did you tell me the radio
at your country place was broken?

01:13:03.797 --> 01:13:06.049
- Because it was broken.
- Not when I tried it.

01:13:06.132 --> 01:13:08.972
Just as I was leaving the village,
I asked the local handyman to fix it.

01:13:09.052 --> 01:13:10.512
How did he get in?

01:13:10.595 --> 01:13:13.014
I always leave a key under the flowerpot
on the porch.

01:13:13.640 --> 01:13:18.228
You're too intelligent to make up
something I could check so easily

01:13:18.311 --> 01:13:23.149
but you're intelligent enough to have
broken it yourself to strengthen your story.

01:13:23.275 --> 01:13:24.292
The main thing I want to know is

01:13:24.317 --> 01:13:27.028
why you pulled that switch on me
about Carpenter.

01:13:27.153 --> 01:13:30.699
You told me last night
you decided not to marry him.

01:13:30.782 --> 01:13:35.120
- Yes, I guess I did.
- But today it was on again. Why?

01:13:35.203 --> 01:13:39.457
Well, I changed my mind.

01:13:39.541 --> 01:13:44.004
What are you trying to hide? Don't you
realize you're involved in a murder?

01:13:44.087 --> 01:13:46.965
You've got yourself in a jam it's not
going to be easy to get out of,

01:13:47.048 --> 01:13:49.092
unless you're on the level with me.

01:13:49.175 --> 01:13:51.678
This is no time for secrets.

01:13:51.761 --> 01:13:53.888
Now, did you really decide
to call it off

01:13:53.972 --> 01:13:57.559
or did you just tell me that because
you knew I wanted to hear it?

01:14:02.022 --> 01:14:05.150
What went on between you and Carpenter
when you saw him last night?

01:14:05.275 --> 01:14:07.360
Did he persuade you to make up?

01:14:08.987 --> 01:14:11.197
Or did you agree to pretend you had?

01:14:11.281 --> 01:14:14.492
- Was that it?
- Well, we... That is, both of us thought...

01:14:14.576 --> 01:14:17.370
He convinced you that if you
broke the engagement now,

01:14:17.454 --> 01:14:19.998
people would think
you believed he was guilty.

01:14:20.081 --> 01:14:23.585
Yes, but now I know it was only
because he thought I was.

01:14:23.793 --> 01:14:26.796
- Did you believe he was guilty?
- No. I'm sure he isn't.

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:29.799
But he'd gotten himself
into an awfully suspicious position

01:14:29.883 --> 01:14:33.136
and he's the sort of man that people are
always ready to believe the worst about.

01:14:34.721 --> 01:14:36.723
Are you in love with him?

01:14:41.227 --> 01:14:43.063
I don't see how I ever could have been.

01:14:47.776 --> 01:14:49.527
Come on. You're going home.

01:14:51.988 --> 01:14:54.908
- But I thought I was...
- That's what I wanted you to think.

01:14:55.825 --> 01:14:59.037
You and a few others.
I didn't even book you.

01:14:59.120 --> 01:15:01.331
You mean this was some sort of a game?

01:15:01.414 --> 01:15:04.334
I was 99% certain about you

01:15:04.417 --> 01:15:06.753
but I had to get rid of
that one percent doubt.

01:15:06.836 --> 01:15:09.923
Wasn't there
an easier way to make sure?

01:15:10.006 --> 01:15:13.426
I'd reached a point
where I needed official surroundings.

01:15:16.096 --> 01:15:17.597
Then it was worth it, Mark.

01:15:21.101 --> 01:15:22.519
I'll call a cab for you.

01:15:36.241 --> 01:15:38.326
Good night. I'll see you tomorrow.

01:15:38.410 --> 01:15:39.619
Good night, Mark.

01:15:41.621 --> 01:15:43.623
I'm going over to Lydecker's apartment.

01:17:06.748 --> 01:17:08.791
It still doesn't
make sense to me, Laura.

01:17:08.917 --> 01:17:11.085
He's playing some sort
of a game with you.

01:17:11.753 --> 01:17:14.589
- I don't think so.
- I don't deny that he's infatuated with you

01:17:14.672 --> 01:17:17.342
in some warped way of his own.

01:17:17.967 --> 01:17:21.554
But he isn't capable of any normal,
warm human relationship.

01:17:22.055 --> 01:17:25.016
He's been dealing
with criminals too long.

01:17:27.143 --> 01:17:29.479
When you were unattainable,
when he thought you were dead,

01:17:29.771 --> 01:17:31.356
that's when he wanted you most.

01:17:31.439 --> 01:17:33.441
But he was glad when I came back

01:17:33.525 --> 01:17:35.527
as if he were waiting for me.

01:17:35.693 --> 01:17:38.905
Do you know what
he calls women? "Dames."

01:17:39.072 --> 01:17:42.408
A "dame" in Washington Heights
got a fox fur out of him.

01:17:42.617 --> 01:17:45.787
- His very words.
- That doesn't mean anything.

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:47.747
He isn't like that.

01:17:48.540 --> 01:17:50.416
Laura, you have one tragic weakness.

01:17:51.417 --> 01:17:54.504
With you, a lean, strong body
is the measure of a man

01:17:54.587 --> 01:17:56.172
and you always get hurt.

01:17:58.216 --> 01:18:00.134
No man is ever going to hurt me again.

01:18:00.885 --> 01:18:03.012
No one, not even you.

01:18:03.972 --> 01:18:06.849
I? Hurt you?

01:18:07.267 --> 01:18:09.394
Laura, look at me.

01:18:11.938 --> 01:18:15.024
When a man has everything
in the world that he wants,

01:18:15.108 --> 01:18:18.278
except what he wants most,

01:18:18.361 --> 01:18:20.405
he loses his self-respect.

01:18:20.780 --> 01:18:22.615
It makes him bitter, Laura.

01:18:23.783 --> 01:18:26.536
He wants to hurt someone
as he's been hurt.

01:18:28.663 --> 01:18:32.041
You were a long time
in finding out about Shelby,

01:18:32.292 --> 01:18:35.086
but that's over now.

01:18:36.379 --> 01:18:38.214
We'll be back together again.

01:18:40.174 --> 01:18:43.553
Haven't you heard of science's
newest triumph, the doorbell?

01:18:45.263 --> 01:18:46.723
I don't like to remind her.

01:18:48.975 --> 01:18:53.771
- That was the murderer's signal.
- Did you eavesdrop too? I hope.

01:18:53.855 --> 01:18:57.317
I thought you'd like to know. We
tested your shotgun. It isn't the one.

01:18:57.984 --> 01:19:00.361
Now, that's what I call a typical move,

01:19:00.445 --> 01:19:02.947
a real key to the man's character.

01:19:03.573 --> 01:19:05.867
First he tells you that
he thinks you're innocent,

01:19:05.992 --> 01:19:08.036
then proceeds to check up on you.

01:19:08.119 --> 01:19:10.163
When I report that I think
she's innocent,

01:19:10.288 --> 01:19:12.457
that's my own personal opinion.

01:19:12.540 --> 01:19:15.126
When I submit proof, it becomes
the opinion of the department.

01:19:15.335 --> 01:19:18.004
This entire maneuver could be a trick
to get you off your guard.

01:19:18.087 --> 01:19:19.756
It could be, but it isn't.

01:19:19.839 --> 01:19:23.593
- I believe you, Mark.
- It's the same obvious pattern, Laura.

01:19:24.135 --> 01:19:27.680
If McPherson weren't muscular and
handsome in a cheap sort of way,

01:19:27.805 --> 01:19:29.599
you'd see through him in a second.

01:19:29.849 --> 01:19:33.102
Waldo, I mean to be
as kind about this as I know how

01:19:33.186 --> 01:19:37.940
but I must tell you, you're the one who
follows the same obvious pattern.

01:19:38.024 --> 01:19:40.001
First it was Jacoby, then Shelby.
And now I suppose...

01:19:40.026 --> 01:19:41.194
- Laura, I...
- I don't think

01:19:41.277 --> 01:19:42.654
we should see each other again.

01:19:42.737 --> 01:19:46.783
- You're not yourself, darling.
- Yes, I am.

01:19:46.866 --> 01:19:49.869
For the first time in ages,
I know what I'm doing.

01:19:52.664 --> 01:19:54.916
Very well.

01:19:55.041 --> 01:19:57.585
I hope you'll never regret
what promises to be

01:19:57.669 --> 01:20:00.046
a disgustingly earthy relationship.

01:20:02.215 --> 01:20:03.841
My congratulations, McPherson.

01:20:05.051 --> 01:20:07.387
Listen to my broadcast in 15 minutes.

01:20:08.388 --> 01:20:10.723
I'm discussing great lovers of history.

01:20:31.953 --> 01:20:34.997
It was the most difficult thing
I ever had to do in my whole life.

01:20:36.290 --> 01:20:38.167
All I need is the gun.

01:20:43.005 --> 01:20:44.298
What are you doing?

01:20:44.382 --> 01:20:46.342
Do you know the combination
to this thing?

01:20:47.260 --> 01:20:50.972
- I never knew it had one.
- It must be somewhere. Oh.

01:21:02.775 --> 01:21:05.611
- Have you ever seen this before?
- No.

01:21:06.946 --> 01:21:08.448
Waldo gave you that clock, didn't he?

01:21:10.032 --> 01:21:11.534
Yes.

01:21:13.035 --> 01:21:15.163
The doorbell rang

01:21:15.371 --> 01:21:18.207
and Diane Redfern
went to the door in your negligee.

01:21:19.792 --> 01:21:23.129
She opened the door. The room was dark.

01:21:24.797 --> 01:21:27.759
Waldo saw a girl standing there,
and he assumed it was you.

01:21:28.968 --> 01:21:31.053
He figured that if
he couldn't have you himself,

01:21:31.137 --> 01:21:32.972
he was gonna make sure
that nobody else did.

01:21:33.097 --> 01:21:35.141
So he let her have it

01:21:38.728 --> 01:21:40.813
with both barrels, right in the face.

01:21:43.065 --> 01:21:44.817
She fell here.

01:21:45.985 --> 01:21:48.279
Waldo heard Shelby running
from the next room

01:21:48.821 --> 01:21:51.199
so he hid in the stairway outside.

01:21:53.284 --> 01:21:56.078
Shelby was scared,
so he ran out as fast as he could.

01:21:56.204 --> 01:21:58.998
Then Waldo came back
and placed the gun in that clock.

01:22:01.542 --> 01:22:03.628
I knew it.

01:22:03.961 --> 01:22:06.172
I've felt it ever since I came back

01:22:06.255 --> 01:22:08.674
but I didn't want to believe it.

01:22:08.966 --> 01:22:11.677
I couldn't make myself believe that

01:22:11.844 --> 01:22:14.013
Waldo was a murderer.

01:22:14.639 --> 01:22:18.351
- Well, he is.
- He didn't really kill Diane Redfern.

01:22:18.851 --> 01:22:20.770
- I killed her.
- What are you talking about?

01:22:21.020 --> 01:22:25.691
But I did, Mark. I did as surely
as if I'd pulled the trigger myself.

01:22:25.775 --> 01:22:27.527
That's nonsense. Forget it.

01:22:27.693 --> 01:22:31.614
No, Mark, I can't.
I'm as guilty as he is,

01:22:31.739 --> 01:22:35.701
not for anything I did,
but for what I didn't do.

01:22:37.411 --> 01:22:41.457
But I couldn't help myself.
I owed him too much.

01:22:46.587 --> 01:22:48.965
I can understand that, Laura,

01:22:49.048 --> 01:22:50.967
but I can't understand why
you've tried so hard

01:22:51.050 --> 01:22:52.718
to protect Shelby these last few days.

01:22:52.802 --> 01:22:55.054
I was nearly frantic for fear
you'd arrest Shelby.

01:22:55.221 --> 01:22:58.266
I knew he wasn't guilty.
He hasn't enough courage to kill a fly.

01:22:58.391 --> 01:23:01.394
And Waldo was doing everything
he could to incriminate him.

01:23:01.561 --> 01:23:03.604
It was his way
of getting rid of Shelby,

01:23:03.729 --> 01:23:05.273
just as he did Jacoby.

01:23:08.734 --> 01:23:10.903
I must say, for a charming,
intelligent girl,

01:23:10.987 --> 01:23:14.282
you've certainly surrounded yourself
with a remarkable collection of dopes.

01:23:16.033 --> 01:23:18.828
Don't touch anything.
Fingerprints will be important.

01:23:21.122 --> 01:23:22.790
I'll have the clock picked up tomorrow.

01:23:23.249 --> 01:23:25.293
- What are you going to do?
- Arrest Waldo.

01:23:25.418 --> 01:23:28.087
- Mark.
- Can't be helped.

01:23:34.468 --> 01:23:36.762
That's to make sure
you're not disturbed.

01:23:37.263 --> 01:23:39.015
If the doorbell rings, don't answer it.

01:23:39.724 --> 01:23:42.310
- I'll phone you in the morning.
- Good night, Mark.

01:23:43.644 --> 01:23:46.814
Get some sleep. Forget
the whole thing like a bad dream.

01:25:39.218 --> 01:25:42.888
<i>And thus,
as history has proved, love is eternal.</i>

01:25:44.015 --> 01:25:47.309
<i>It has been the strongest motivation
for human actions</i>

01:25:47.393 --> 01:25:49.186
<i>throughout centuries.</i>

01:25:49.562 --> 01:25:51.397
<i>Love is stronger than life.</i>

01:25:52.231 --> 01:25:54.859
<i>It reaches beyond
the dark shadow of death.</i>

01:25:56.569 --> 01:25:58.404
<i>I close this evening's broadcast</i>

01:25:58.529 --> 01:26:01.490
<i>with some favorite lines from Dowson.</i>

01:26:01.615 --> 01:26:03.701
<i>Brief Life.</i>

01:26:05.327 --> 01:26:09.373
<i>"They are not long,
the weeping and the laughter,</i>

01:26:09.540 --> 01:26:12.585
<i>"love and desire and hate.</i>

01:26:13.836 --> 01:26:16.047
<i>"I think they have no portion in us</i>

01:26:16.380 --> 01:26:18.257
<i>"after we pass the gate."</i>

01:26:19.425 --> 01:26:22.720
- Who's tailing Lydecker?
- I was going to, when he came out.

01:26:22.887 --> 01:26:25.765
- He left five minutes ago.
- He didn't come out this way.

01:26:25.931 --> 01:26:28.267
Must've gone out the back way.
Come on. Let's check.

01:26:29.685 --> 01:26:33.856
RADIO, CONTINUING: <i>"They are
not long, the days of wine and roses.</i>

01:26:34.815 --> 01:26:38.986
<i>"Out of a misty dream,
our path emerges for a while,</i>

01:26:39.111 --> 01:26:41.030
<i>"then closes within a dream."</i>

01:26:43.324 --> 01:26:45.826
- That's the way it is, isn't it, Laura?
- Waldo!

01:26:45.910 --> 01:26:48.370
<i>You have
heard the voice of Waldo Lydecker</i>

01:26:48.454 --> 01:26:49.997
<i>by electrical transcription.</i>

01:26:50.581 --> 01:26:54.460
Waldo, you've taken one life.
Isn't that enough?

01:26:55.002 --> 01:26:58.297
The best part of myself,
that's what you are.

01:26:59.340 --> 01:27:02.176
Do you think I'm going to leave it
to the vulgar pawing

01:27:02.259 --> 01:27:05.429
of a second-rate detective
who thinks you're a dame?

01:27:05.513 --> 01:27:08.265
Do you think I could bear the thought
of him holding you in his arms,

01:27:08.349 --> 01:27:10.893
kissing you, loving you?

01:27:11.977 --> 01:27:14.313
Laura! It's Mark. Open the door!

01:27:14.480 --> 01:27:16.148
- There he is now.
- Laura!

01:27:16.440 --> 01:27:19.443
He'll find us together, Laura,

01:27:19.902 --> 01:27:23.155
as we always have been, as we always
should be, as we always will be.

01:27:31.247 --> 01:27:33.165
Mark!

01:27:44.343 --> 01:27:45.678
Good-bye, Laura.

01:27:55.396 --> 01:27:58.190
Good-bye, my love.
